[TYPEWRITER DINGS]

00:52.791 --> 00:54.258
[CARRIAGE RETURN CREAKS]

00:54.426 --> 00:56.758
[TYPEWRITER KEYS CLACKING]

01:08.040 --> 01:10.838
[TYPEWRITER KEYS CLACKING]

01:37.603 --> 01:38.763
[TYPEWRITER DINGS]

01:38.937 --> 01:41.371
[TYPEWRITER KEYS CLACKING]

01:58.857 --> 02:01.883
KIT:
<i>It was May 2nd, 1934.</i>

02:02.060 --> 02:05.757
<i>Even though the Great Depression</i>
<i>was in full swing around the world...</i>

02:05.931 --> 02:08.832
<i>... it still seemed far away</i>
<i>from the world I knew.</i>

02:09.300 --> 02:12.464
<i>I was focused on one thing.</i>

02:12.638 --> 02:15.300
<i>I wanted to be a reporter.</i>

02:20.946 --> 02:23.540
[STREETCAR BELL RINGS]

02:32.624 --> 02:34.285
[CAR HORN HONKS]

02:36.328 --> 02:41.698
KIT: <i>I was more excited that day</i>
<i>than I'd ever been in my whole life.</i>

02:44.069 --> 02:48.631
DRIVER: Next up, Clifton and Ludlow.
Everybody up for Clifton and Ludlow.

02:50.275 --> 02:53.642
KIT: <i>If I hurried, I'd have just enough time</i>
<i>to see Dad at his car dealership.</i>

02:55.180 --> 02:58.343
KIT:
Dad. Dad. Dad, look, I finished my article.

02:58.517 --> 03:00.508
That's great, honey. Oh!

03:00.686 --> 03:02.244
[JACK LAUGHS]

03:02.421 --> 03:04.616
- Wish me luck.
- You can do it, sweetheart.

03:04.790 --> 03:06.314
Go get them.

03:08.460 --> 03:10.451
She's gonna be a reporter, that one.

03:10.629 --> 03:11.823
You just wait and see.

03:13.365 --> 03:16.027
Hobo crime spree
spreading across Ohio Valley.

03:16.201 --> 03:19.398
Come get your paper. Hobo crime spree.

03:19.571 --> 03:21.129
Hobo crime spree spreading...

03:21.306 --> 03:24.503
KIT: <i>My brother Charlie</i>
<i>had arranged an introduction...</i>

03:24.843 --> 03:27.835
<i>... at the</i> Cincinnati Register.

03:31.149 --> 03:33.845
<i>Though I was going inside as a visitor...</i>

03:34.286 --> 03:38.052
<i>... I was certain I'd come out a journalist.</i>

03:42.027 --> 03:45.554
<i>How could I have known</i>
<i>what life had in store?</i>

03:45.731 --> 03:48.757
<i>I thought I was ready.</i>

03:49.268 --> 03:50.997
MAN:
Seven, please?

03:56.475 --> 04:00.070
Excuse me, Mr. Peabody? Sir?

04:00.245 --> 04:02.577
- Charlie Kittredge's sister.
- Yes, sir, I'm Kit.

04:02.748 --> 04:06.479
Uh, Billy, and I'm only 19. I'm not
a sir yet. But thanks. Uh, follow me.

04:06.885 --> 04:10.150
Charlie said you wanted
to see a real newsroom, and this is it.

04:10.322 --> 04:12.415
KIT:
Wow, the <i>Cincinnati Register.</i>

04:12.591 --> 04:15.890
- Okay. So where's the editor?
- Uh, Gibson? Right there, why?

04:16.361 --> 04:19.421
I've written this article,
and I'd like for you to give it to him.

04:20.132 --> 04:23.499
- Uh, you'd like me to what?
- Give it to him, you know, to publish.

04:23.669 --> 04:25.102
You're kidding.

04:25.637 --> 04:27.798
You're not kidding. She's not kidding.

04:27.973 --> 04:31.067
I'm not kidding.
It's about the Chicago World's Fair.

04:31.243 --> 04:34.144
I've interviewed several people
who've actually been there.

04:34.313 --> 04:35.439
Eyewitnesses.

04:35.614 --> 04:38.242
Heh. That's what this is about?
You want an article published?

04:38.417 --> 04:39.441
Yes, thank you.

04:39.618 --> 04:42.485
Kid, you don't waltz up to the editor
of the <i>Cincinnati Register...</i>

04:42.654 --> 04:45.487
...and expect him to publish your article.

04:45.657 --> 04:51.493
GIBSON: The tragedy is the fact that
I paid you at all to write this drivel!

04:51.663 --> 04:54.791
I want something new.
I want something fresh.

04:54.967 --> 04:57.731
I want something real before I...

04:57.903 --> 04:59.632
But how about I take a look at it?

04:59.805 --> 05:02.000
Thanks, Billy, would you?

05:03.208 --> 05:04.971
I'll just wait here.

05:05.143 --> 05:07.304
- Ha, ha.
- But you take your time.

05:07.479 --> 05:08.844
Uh, no.

05:09.014 --> 05:11.608
You can come back another time.

05:12.551 --> 05:13.779
That works too.

05:13.952 --> 05:15.442
KIT:
<i>He's just reading it, Ruthie.</i>

05:15.621 --> 05:17.953
He might not even give it to Mr. Gibson.
Who knows?

05:18.123 --> 05:21.286
- You're late. Let's go.
- Does Mother know you're coming with me?

05:21.460 --> 05:24.861
Mother,
I'm going to Kit's house with Frances!

05:25.030 --> 05:27.521
- Yes, dear.
- Now she does.

05:33.005 --> 05:34.529
Good day.

05:35.607 --> 05:37.074
KIT:
Come on, let's go.

05:37.242 --> 05:39.437
[SINGING] <i>I'm being sworn</i>
<i>Into the Treehouse Club</i>

05:39.611 --> 05:42.546
- <i>I'm being sworn into the Treehouse Club.</i>
- Afternoon.

05:43.982 --> 05:45.540
Hello.

05:45.751 --> 05:49.744
You all know if the people who live here
might be interested in a barter?

05:49.988 --> 05:52.388
KIT: Depends.
RUTHIE: What's a barter?

05:52.557 --> 05:53.581
A trade.

05:54.059 --> 05:56.960
See, my partner here and I'll work for food
and...

05:57.129 --> 06:00.394
- Anyways, I'm Will, and this is Countee.
- Hey.

06:00.999 --> 06:03.934
Mother's out back with her Garden Club.
Follow me.

06:04.102 --> 06:06.570
FLORENCE [SINGING]: <i>I'm being sworn</i>
<i>Into the Treehouse Club.</i>

06:06.738 --> 06:10.538
MR. STONE: Everything will be okay.
Everything will be fine.

06:16.982 --> 06:19.007
I just heard you're moving, Louise.

06:19.184 --> 06:20.481
My husband left weeks ago...

06:20.652 --> 06:23.553
...and we're staying at the Netherland
until he sends for us.

06:23.722 --> 06:25.781
The Netherland Plaza Hotel?

06:25.957 --> 06:27.515
I heard it's magnificent.

06:27.693 --> 06:29.285
We'd love to see the rooms.

06:29.828 --> 06:31.523
Margaret, look.

06:31.697 --> 06:32.891
KIT:
Mother.

06:33.065 --> 06:35.693
WOMAN:
Hobos. We cannot trust them.

06:38.770 --> 06:40.260
Hello.

06:40.439 --> 06:41.736
How can I help you?

06:41.907 --> 06:46.105
- Mother, this is Will and his friend...
WILL: Countee.

06:46.278 --> 06:49.736
And they're looking to make a barter,
which means work for food.

06:49.915 --> 06:51.940
I can pretty much fix anything broke.

06:52.617 --> 06:54.141
Windows, uh...

06:54.319 --> 06:57.584
...fences, any kind of machine.

06:57.756 --> 07:00.486
We're trustworthy and responsible.

07:00.659 --> 07:02.320
MARGARET:
Come back in the morning.

07:02.761 --> 07:04.991
- We'll see what we can do.
WILL: Thank you.

07:05.564 --> 07:07.156
One moment.

07:09.501 --> 07:11.059
WOMAN:
Don't feed them, Margaret.

07:11.236 --> 07:12.328
[WOMEN GASP]

07:12.504 --> 07:15.098
MARGARET: Why don't you take
something to eat before you leave?

07:15.273 --> 07:17.503
Thank you, ma'am,
but, uh, we only take when we work.

07:17.876 --> 07:19.434
I can't let you leave hungry.

07:19.611 --> 07:23.411
Better be quick. I've already seen
Mrs. Culver dive headfirst into the nuts.

07:23.949 --> 07:26.440
Who knows what she'll do
when she sees the sandwiches?

07:26.818 --> 07:28.445
Please, take it as an advance.

07:29.321 --> 07:30.447
Go on.

07:30.622 --> 07:33.090
All right, as an advance. Thank you.

07:33.258 --> 07:36.455
- We'll be working it off in the morning.
- See you then.

07:36.928 --> 07:39.089
WILL: Let's go, Countee.
- Ahem.

07:40.565 --> 07:44.228
My husband says let them go hungry.
It's the only way to keep them out of town.

07:44.402 --> 07:45.926
MARGARET:
Oh, Louise.

07:46.204 --> 07:49.230
Can't help but think
that those boys are someone's children too.

07:49.407 --> 07:50.669
MRS. CULVER:
Hmm.

07:51.309 --> 07:53.277
COUNTEE:
Will, come on.

07:54.946 --> 07:57.710
KIT:
Okay, everybody. In your places.

07:59.251 --> 08:00.946
FLORENCE:
"Member-o-belia."

08:02.287 --> 08:05.188
Eleanor Roosevelt. Amelia Earhart.

08:05.657 --> 08:07.716
Kit, Ruthie, Frances...

08:07.893 --> 08:10.521
...and soon, Florence.

08:10.695 --> 08:12.526
KIT:
Do you, Florence Stone...

08:12.964 --> 08:16.730
...swear to be true to the Treehouse Club
and only the Treehouse Club...

08:17.169 --> 08:19.296
...as long as you shall live?

08:19.471 --> 08:20.836
I do.

08:21.006 --> 08:25.375
And if anyone should ask you
to join the 9th Street Club?

08:25.844 --> 08:28.574
I will laugh in their faces.

08:28.747 --> 08:31.739
[WHISPERS]
You're supposed to say, "I will decline."

08:32.150 --> 08:34.140
I will decline...

08:34.318 --> 08:36.219
...and laugh.
- Ha, ha.

08:37.889 --> 08:41.985
Now Ruthie will get the sacred water
off the sacred shelf.

08:42.159 --> 08:44.355
I already did. It's in the sacred bowl.

08:44.796 --> 08:46.127
KIT:
Good.

08:46.298 --> 08:50.428
Now Treehouse members
and potential Treehouse members...

08:50.602 --> 08:54.368
...take your right hand,
and place it in the bowl.

08:57.609 --> 08:59.076
We are one.

09:01.146 --> 09:04.047
Now place two fingers
over your heart, like so...

09:04.749 --> 09:07.946
...for the sacred Treehouse pledge.

09:08.220 --> 09:10.051
All together:

09:10.222 --> 09:13.020
ALL:
Gwanga, gwanga, galoolie...

09:13.191 --> 09:16.319
...kariba, kariba, kariv.

09:16.494 --> 09:18.928
- I swear to be true to the...
MR. STONE: Betty Lou!

09:19.097 --> 09:20.792
MRS. STONE:
Robert, do something!

09:22.400 --> 09:24.493
MAN 1: Sir...?
MAN 2: Yep.

09:24.903 --> 09:27.633
MR. STONE: We're gonna be okay then.
MAN: No, save that.

09:27.939 --> 09:30.999
- Frances, look.
KIT: That's your bed.

09:31.176 --> 09:33.007
- What does that mean?
MRS. STONE: My furniture.

09:33.178 --> 09:36.773
"Foreclosure by order of the bank."

09:36.948 --> 09:39.041
That means
the bank's taking our house away.

09:40.385 --> 09:42.819
Ruthie, isn't that your father's bank?

09:43.221 --> 09:45.416
Can you ask your father to give it back?

09:46.791 --> 09:51.194
Just let them go. Betty Lou!
Just let them go.

09:54.532 --> 09:57.865
Oh, what a pity. I had no idea.

09:58.036 --> 10:00.436
Well, he lost his job months ago,
Lorraine.

10:00.605 --> 10:03.267
They've been selling eggs just to get by.

10:04.976 --> 10:08.434
- Will you excuse me?
MR. STONE: You just let them go, okay?

10:08.780 --> 10:10.077
Come on, let's go.

10:10.248 --> 10:13.945
But my picture's not up
on the member-o-belia wall yet.

10:14.119 --> 10:15.848
Florence.

10:22.427 --> 10:25.260
MR. STONE:
Everybody's watching, Lou.

10:25.430 --> 10:27.762
[MRS. STONE CRYING]

10:31.303 --> 10:32.702
MARGARET:
Betty Lou.

10:32.871 --> 10:34.429
[CRYING]

10:34.606 --> 10:36.198
MARGARET:
Oh, I'm so sorry.

10:36.374 --> 10:38.342
MR. STONE: Come on.
- Where will they go?

10:38.510 --> 10:40.444
I don't know.

10:41.780 --> 10:44.271
I'm so sorry, Barbara.

10:50.789 --> 10:53.053
[CAR HORN HONKS]

10:59.297 --> 11:01.731
JACK:
There she is. How's my girl?

11:01.900 --> 11:03.527
- Dad, Dad.
- Come here.

11:03.702 --> 11:04.964
[JACK GRUNTS]

11:05.136 --> 11:06.398
[JACK CHUCKLES]

11:06.938 --> 11:09.964
- What's the matter?
- Dad, look.

11:11.876 --> 11:15.209
"The Stones lose their house."

11:20.752 --> 11:23.220
RUTHIE: <i>And that's why my</i>
<i>favorite stories are fairy tales...</i>

11:23.555 --> 11:26.353
...because no matter how scary it gets...

11:26.524 --> 11:28.651
...everybody always lives happily
ever after.

11:30.161 --> 11:32.493
And often with some very nice outfits.

11:32.664 --> 11:34.859
[GIRLS CHUCKLE, BOYS GROAN]

11:35.767 --> 11:39.601
Thank you, Ruthie. Thank you.
Thank you, Ruthie.

11:41.139 --> 11:44.074
Does, uh... Does anyone know
where Frances Stone is?

11:44.242 --> 11:45.436
KIT:
She's away.

11:45.610 --> 11:48.078
Staying with family.

11:48.246 --> 11:51.579
- Yeah, in a hobo jungle somewhere.
- Stop it, Roger.

11:51.750 --> 11:54.514
Frances Stone is a good-for-nothing,
deadbeat egg seller...

11:54.686 --> 11:57.655
...and everyone knows it.
She wore dresses made of feed sacks.

11:57.822 --> 12:01.053
Roger. Ruthie, not another word.

12:01.760 --> 12:04.524
Well, this seems like an opportune time
to let you know...

12:04.696 --> 12:07.529
...that as a final class assignment
before summer vacation...

12:07.699 --> 12:10.031
...we're going to help out
at a soup kitchen...

12:10.201 --> 12:12.533
...where they provide food
for the poor and needy.

12:12.704 --> 12:14.262
Uh, Roger.

12:14.439 --> 12:16.532
My dad says that people
eat at soup kitchens...

12:16.708 --> 12:20.144
...are hobos who feed off the government.
That's why we're in a depression.

12:20.545 --> 12:22.479
I understand, Roger.

12:22.647 --> 12:26.014
Therefore,
anyone who doesn't wish to help out...

12:26.184 --> 12:29.711
...can write a 1 500- word essay
on the history of volunteerism.

12:29.888 --> 12:31.685
[STUDENTS LAUGH]

12:31.856 --> 12:34.416
Roger's leading my team
for the soup kitchen.

12:34.592 --> 12:35.786
Why, he's a nice boy.

12:35.960 --> 12:40.488
He's a horrible boy. He just didn't want
to have to do that paper.

12:40.665 --> 12:41.654
[GASPS]

12:41.833 --> 12:43.562
[WHINES]

12:44.302 --> 12:47.931
Mother, look. She's all alone.

12:48.106 --> 12:50.336
MARGARET:
Oh. Poor thing.

12:52.977 --> 12:56.003
"Grace. Can't feed her anymore."

12:57.982 --> 12:59.347
Can we take her?

13:00.018 --> 13:01.076
Wha...? No.

13:01.252 --> 13:05.780
She can be my birthday present for this year
and next year...

13:05.957 --> 13:07.083
...and forever.

13:07.258 --> 13:09.021
I'm sorry, sweetheart.

13:12.330 --> 13:13.661
Wha...? What's that, Grace?

13:13.832 --> 13:16.096
- Ha-ha-ha.
KIT: Mm-hm. Mm-hm.

13:17.502 --> 13:19.333
Okay, I'll tell her.

13:19.504 --> 13:22.598
She said she'll be very quiet
and only eat scraps...

13:22.774 --> 13:24.435
- Mm-hm.
- and be the very best dog...

13:24.609 --> 13:25.974
...you could ever hope to have.

13:27.812 --> 13:34.115
Can we at least bring her home
for one teeny-weeny meaningless night?

13:34.285 --> 13:36.549
How can you say no to that face?

13:37.088 --> 13:38.953
Mother.

13:39.791 --> 13:41.156
Please, please, please.

13:41.793 --> 13:43.454
All right, but one night only.

13:44.262 --> 13:47.459
She said yes. She said yes.
You're coming home.

13:49.767 --> 13:51.962
I'll take care of you. Don't worry.

13:54.739 --> 13:57.037
MAN 1:
Help! Stop him!

13:57.208 --> 13:59.642
WOMAN 1: Help, stop, stop him.
MAN 1: Help!

13:59.811 --> 14:02.245
WOMAN 2: Stop him. Police.
MAN 2: What happened?

14:02.413 --> 14:05.348
Did you see that? In broad daylight.

14:05.517 --> 14:07.712
- He took my wallet.
- Are you all right?

14:08.186 --> 14:10.586
MAN: Yes, ma'am.
- What color was your wallet?

14:10.755 --> 14:13.815
It was red. My son made it for me.

14:13.992 --> 14:15.857
Did you see that tattoo on his arm?

14:16.027 --> 14:18.222
It was odd. Something like a bird, maybe.

14:18.530 --> 14:20.862
It was so fast,
I didn't really get to see it all.

14:21.032 --> 14:25.366
All I noticed was that he was a hobo.

14:28.039 --> 14:29.506
[WHISPERS]
Get your dog.

14:35.680 --> 14:37.910
I had a late lunch today, Margaret.

14:38.583 --> 14:39.777
Save it for leftovers.

14:43.388 --> 14:46.186
- Uncle Hendrick, more meatloaf?
- Thank you, no.

14:46.357 --> 14:49.849
I'll tell you this, Jack, keep supporting
your president and his New Deal...

14:50.028 --> 14:52.553
...and you'll see what'll happen
to this country.

14:52.730 --> 14:53.992
Your own son quit college.

14:54.165 --> 14:58.033
Well, he didn't quit. He postponed.
Right, Dad?

14:58.203 --> 15:01.263
HENDRICK:
To join one of these newfangled programs.

15:01.439 --> 15:06.342
CCC is a great program, Hendrick.
Charlie is building parks and fixing roads...

15:06.511 --> 15:10.242
And sending money home
because business is a little slow.

15:10.782 --> 15:12.977
There's no shame
in families helping each other.

15:13.151 --> 15:14.846
Hmm.

15:15.019 --> 15:17.385
Hard to think of you this way, Margaret.

15:17.555 --> 15:19.580
Saving leftovers.

15:20.525 --> 15:22.390
We like leftovers.

15:23.861 --> 15:28.321
- I should be leaving.
- Oh, no. Please. Stay longer.

15:28.499 --> 15:30.865
Ha-ha-ha.
You think I'm the voice of doom, Jack.

15:31.035 --> 15:33.902
But I'll tell you this.
When people live beyond their means...

15:34.072 --> 15:36.734
...in houses that are too big
for their pockets...

15:36.908 --> 15:38.341
[GRACE WHINES]

15:38.509 --> 15:39.942
What's that noise?

15:40.111 --> 15:43.137
Oh, you haven't met our newest addition,
Grace.

15:43.314 --> 15:45.714
KIT: She's normally very quiet,
Uncle Hendrick.

15:45.883 --> 15:48.852
JACK: Except for when she snores.
MARGARET: And the drool.

15:49.020 --> 15:53.354
It seems to me the last thing you need
is another mouth to feed.

15:53.858 --> 15:56.691
Well, luckily, she doesn't eat very much.

15:56.861 --> 15:57.850
[GRACE SIGHS]

15:58.029 --> 15:59.428
KIT:
Come on, Grace. Come on.

15:59.597 --> 16:02.464
Good girl.

16:02.634 --> 16:04.192
[GRACE WHINES]

16:07.071 --> 16:10.939
Shouldn't you fellows be getting on back
to wherever it is you live?

16:11.743 --> 16:13.335
Yes, sir.

16:15.346 --> 16:17.371
What's the capital of North Dakota?
Quick.

16:17.548 --> 16:18.606
Bismarck.

16:19.584 --> 16:21.814
Make sure your mother
doesn't work too hard.

16:29.360 --> 16:32.727
[CLIFF EDWARDS' "IT'S ONLY
A PAPER MOON" PLAYING ON RADIO]

16:39.437 --> 16:43.464
RUTHIE: I can't believe that none of
these people have money for food.

16:45.009 --> 16:47.671
You come over here and chop that bread up
for everybody...

16:47.845 --> 16:50.313
...back of the line, right there.

17:02.860 --> 17:05.761
[BABY CRYING]

17:10.867 --> 17:14.598
- Would you like some bread?
WOMAN 1: Thanks, sweetheart.

17:14.771 --> 17:16.364
WOMAN 2:
Excuse me.

17:44.502 --> 17:46.060
Dad.

18:24.776 --> 18:26.334
[JACK SIGHS]

18:27.812 --> 18:29.109
JACK:
Tried.

18:34.886 --> 18:36.251
JACK:
How is she?

18:36.421 --> 18:39.083
Uh, she's... She's up in the tree house.

18:47.732 --> 18:49.165
JACK:
Kit.

18:52.570 --> 18:54.162
Kit, I know you're up there.

18:55.173 --> 18:58.006
I understand if you're angry with me...

18:58.176 --> 19:00.144
...or, uh, embarrassed.

19:00.945 --> 19:04.779
Please come down, sweetheart.
I'd like to explain.

19:08.419 --> 19:09.784
Kit.

19:33.110 --> 19:34.304
[SIGHS]

19:34.479 --> 19:35.673
Kit.

19:43.754 --> 19:45.244
Why were you there, Dad?

19:45.423 --> 19:47.015
[SIGHS]

19:48.793 --> 19:51.023
The bank took the car dealership.

19:52.263 --> 19:56.131
- Ruthie's father did that to us?
- Kit.

19:56.434 --> 19:58.095
This isn't personal.

19:59.170 --> 20:00.831
Are we gonna lose the house?

20:02.773 --> 20:04.434
We're gonna be fine.

20:10.548 --> 20:12.345
Where's our car?

20:14.952 --> 20:16.476
Daddy.

20:20.892 --> 20:22.655
JACK [WHISPERS]:
We're gonna be okay.

20:23.561 --> 20:27.554
BOY: Hey, Kit, your father good enough
to eat at the soup kitchen? Ha, ha!

20:27.732 --> 20:28.926
Just ignore them.

20:29.100 --> 20:32.160
And now Kit will probably start
raising chickens, selling eggs...

20:32.336 --> 20:37.035
...and wearing feed-sack dresses,
just like Frances did.

20:37.208 --> 20:38.766
What's a feed-sack dress?

20:38.943 --> 20:41.969
It's a dress made out of the bag
that chicken feed comes in.

20:42.280 --> 20:44.145
Are you really gonna wear one, Kit?

20:44.315 --> 20:47.307
Sure she will.
Right after her family starts selling eggs.

20:47.618 --> 20:49.210
We're not egg sellers.

20:49.387 --> 20:51.787
And then it's just one step
before the poorhouse.

20:51.956 --> 20:54.686
[IMITATING CHICKEN CLUCKING]

20:57.295 --> 21:00.389
BOY: Come get your chicken and
your eggs from Kit Kittredge. Bock, bock!

21:00.565 --> 21:02.226
ROGER:
You're all a bunch of freeloaders.

21:02.400 --> 21:04.163
[GIRLS GASP]

21:04.335 --> 21:07.099
Why don't you come over here
and say that to my face, Roger.

21:07.271 --> 21:10.832
Okay. You're all a bunch of freeloaders!

21:11.542 --> 21:13.237
What's that you've got behind you?

21:13.411 --> 21:15.140
[STUDENTS LAUGHING]

21:15.313 --> 21:17.247
[IMITATING CHICKEN CLUCKING]

21:17.415 --> 21:19.940
KIT:
Got any eggs? Bock, bock, bock!

21:20.117 --> 21:22.176
How much for the eggs, Roger?

21:22.353 --> 21:25.186
Bock, bock, bock!
Look at Mr. Feather Pants.

21:25.356 --> 21:27.950
STUDENTS: Ha-ha-ha!
- And how's our mural...

21:28.125 --> 21:29.592
[STUDENTS GASP]

21:29.927 --> 21:30.951
...coming?

21:31.128 --> 21:34.859
KIT: But, Mother, it was Roger's fault.
- Oh, Kit.

21:35.032 --> 21:38.092
Please don't take everything
people say so personally.

21:39.003 --> 21:41.164
Everyone's in trouble these days.

21:41.339 --> 21:44.103
JACK: In fact, we've had to move
your things into the attic.

21:44.475 --> 21:47.000
KIT:
The attic? Why?

21:47.178 --> 21:50.306
Your mother and I have decided
we're gonna take in boarders.

21:51.716 --> 21:54.082
Boarders? Like...

21:54.251 --> 21:55.513
...strangers?

21:55.686 --> 22:01.283
That are gonna come and live in our house
and eat our food and sit on our sofa?

22:01.626 --> 22:04.288
There's no shame in it, honey.

22:04.462 --> 22:06.657
Lots of people are doing it to get by.

22:06.831 --> 22:09.163
We're not gonna start selling eggs,
are we?

22:09.333 --> 22:11.301
Ha, ha. We hadn't planned on it.

22:12.169 --> 22:15.332
This is only temporary, sweetheart,
I promise.

22:15.506 --> 22:16.871
You know...

22:17.041 --> 22:18.338
...once I get to Chicago...

22:18.743 --> 22:22.611
...I'll find a good-paying job,
just as quick as you can say "Plymouth."

22:22.780 --> 22:24.008
Chicago?

22:24.315 --> 22:26.044
What? You're leaving?

22:26.217 --> 22:27.707
- I have some good leads in...
- No.

22:28.285 --> 22:29.445
- No.
- Kit.

22:29.620 --> 22:32.111
You said we were going to be okay.

22:32.289 --> 22:34.849
We're not okay if we're not together.

22:39.063 --> 22:40.894
[GROANS]

22:42.366 --> 22:43.890
[KIT GROANS]

22:45.436 --> 22:47.097
[GRUNTS]

22:48.839 --> 22:50.067
Ah.

22:50.241 --> 22:51.606
Don't let it beat you, Kit.

22:54.311 --> 22:55.869
You know, when I was about 14...

22:56.280 --> 23:00.512
...my dad traded some old farm equipment
for a used Model T.

23:00.685 --> 23:03.279
One time I was cranking it, to start it...

23:04.221 --> 23:06.655
...and the crank broke in half.

23:07.058 --> 23:10.255
Car kind of groaned,
and it just died right in our front yard.

23:11.328 --> 23:13.922
I wanted to junk the darn thing
when my dad walked in...

23:14.765 --> 23:17.359
...and he said,
"Don't let it beat you, son."

23:17.968 --> 23:19.902
Don't let it beat you.

23:20.571 --> 23:23.404
Drove it for five more years after that.

23:24.375 --> 23:27.435
So whether it's an old Model T...

23:27.745 --> 23:30.111
...or a typewriter ribbon...

23:31.415 --> 23:35.283
...or going to Chicago to find work...

23:39.590 --> 23:41.558
...we can't let it beat us, sweetheart.

23:42.727 --> 23:43.751
Come on.

23:44.395 --> 23:46.124
It's time for bed.

23:50.735 --> 23:52.498
[SIGHS]

23:54.371 --> 23:56.601
What if you don't come back?

23:58.843 --> 24:00.276
[SIGHS]

24:07.384 --> 24:09.716
I, Jack Kittredge...

24:09.887 --> 24:10.945
...do solemnly swear...

24:11.555 --> 24:14.422
...that I will write you once a week.

24:14.792 --> 24:16.919
And that there is nothing in this world...

24:17.094 --> 24:19.426
...that could ever keep me
from coming back to you.

24:20.965 --> 24:23.297
Do you promise, Dad?

24:23.467 --> 24:25.162
Really promise?

24:25.703 --> 24:27.637
I do.

24:28.839 --> 24:31.171
Gwanga, gwanga, galoolie...

24:33.711 --> 24:36.771
Kariba, kariba, kariv.

24:42.119 --> 24:44.383
I love you, Dad.

24:45.389 --> 24:48.950
- I love you.
- I love you too, sweetheart.

24:55.633 --> 24:57.624
[KIT CRYING]

24:57.802 --> 24:59.702
[BUS ENGINE STARTS]

25:03.974 --> 25:05.737
[MOUTHS]
<i>Bye.</i>

25:05.910 --> 25:08.140
[CRYING]

25:23.994 --> 25:27.020
KIT:
<i>June 17th, 1934. Dear Dad.</i>

25:27.965 --> 25:32.493
<i>Thanks for the letter. We miss you too</i>
<i>and hope you're finding work in Chicago.</i>

25:32.670 --> 25:34.297
<i>Here at home, things are hopping.</i>

25:34.471 --> 25:38.168
<i>School's out, and I can't call my friends</i>
<i>because the phone's been disconnected.</i>

25:38.342 --> 25:39.366
No phone?

25:39.543 --> 25:43.570
KIT: <i>So now all I do is clean</i>
<i>and sweep and fold...</i>

25:43.747 --> 25:46.409
<i>... and iron and wipe and cook.</i>

25:46.584 --> 25:49.747
<i>And fold and clean and sweep and iron</i>
<i>and wipe and cook some more.</i>

25:49.920 --> 25:53.981
<i>My grand plans for being a real reporter</i>
<i>are kind of on the back burner.</i>

25:54.158 --> 25:57.525
<i>Don't get me wrong, Dad.</i>
<i>I'm not complaining. I'm just...</i>

25:57.695 --> 26:00.687
<i>... well, complaining.</i>

26:02.466 --> 26:05.526
<i>The house is chock-full of boarders,</i>
<i>which keeps us pretty busy.</i>

26:06.070 --> 26:09.733
<i>Mrs. Howard and her son, Stirling,</i>
<i>moved into my bedroom.</i>

26:12.309 --> 26:13.640
We're almost there, lamby.

26:14.945 --> 26:17.038
BOTH [WHISPER]:
Lamby.

26:17.414 --> 26:20.713
KIT: <i>It's going to be strange</i>
<i>having a boy from my class living here.</i>

26:20.885 --> 26:22.648
<i>But I guess I'll get used to it.</i>

26:23.120 --> 26:26.419
<i>Mother moved into the sewing room</i>
<i>so we can squeeze in another border.</i>

26:26.590 --> 26:28.455
<i>I thought that was very clever of her.</i>

26:28.993 --> 26:31.018
<i>Now your room belongs to Miss Dooley...</i>

26:31.195 --> 26:34.995
<i>... a dance instructor</i>
<i>who likes to practice her steps out back.</i>

26:35.165 --> 26:38.259
<i>Though, I'm not at all sure</i>
<i>Mrs. Howard approves.</i>

26:39.470 --> 26:41.961
<i>Did you know Mother</i>
<i>divided the living room in half...</i>

26:42.139 --> 26:45.040
<i>... to make room for Miss Bond,</i>
<i>a mobile librarian who moved in last week?</i>

26:45.209 --> 26:46.233
[HORN HONKS]

26:46.410 --> 26:49.345
<i>Now, if she can only learn the difference</i>
<i>between the gas and the brake...</i>

26:49.513 --> 26:50.980
[HORN HONKING]

26:51.148 --> 26:53.139
Oh, take cover!

26:53.951 --> 26:55.578
KIT:
<i>We'll all breathe a little easier.</i>

26:55.753 --> 26:57.914
[HORN HONKING]

27:02.993 --> 27:04.756
Where'd everyone go?

27:04.962 --> 27:06.930
KIT: <i>You'll be happy to know</i>
<i>we've been using...</i>

27:07.097 --> 27:10.089
<i>... Aunt Millie's Waste Not, Want Not tips</i>
<i>to make meals stretch.</i>

27:10.267 --> 27:12.792
<i>Like cutting one piece of toast</i>
<i>into four triangles...</i>

27:12.970 --> 27:15.302
<i>... to make a whole loaf</i>
<i>go for three meals.</i>

27:16.206 --> 27:17.696
<i>Mother says it's magic.</i>

27:17.875 --> 27:21.367
- <i>But the real magician is our newest arrival...</i>
- Jefferson J. Berk...

27:21.612 --> 27:27.175
...master of misdirection, dean of deception,
and escape artist extraordinaire.

27:27.351 --> 27:30.445
Observe.
I need a volunteer from the audience.

27:31.522 --> 27:33.046
Young man.

27:34.224 --> 27:35.589
- What's your name?
- Stirling.

27:35.759 --> 27:36.987
Stirling.

27:37.161 --> 27:39.391
- Do you mind wearing these for a while?
STIRLING: No. No.

27:39.563 --> 27:40.791
BERK:
Come with me.

27:40.965 --> 27:46.961
Notice the strong solid-steel cuffs.
Can you get out of that?

27:47.137 --> 27:49.037
- Are you sure? Are you sure?
- Yeah.

27:49.206 --> 27:50.468
- Are you sure?
CHILDREN: Ha, ha!

27:50.641 --> 27:53.838
The only thing that can get you out of that
is this key.

27:54.345 --> 27:56.336
We hope.
Sometimes it doesn't work though.

27:56.513 --> 27:59.038
And then we have to cut you out of it.

27:59.350 --> 28:03.309
Oh, there we are. All right, now,
would you hold this key for me, please?

28:03.487 --> 28:04.545
KIT:
Yes.

28:05.055 --> 28:07.990
BERK: Don't lose it.
Will you put these on my wrists, please?

28:08.158 --> 28:09.557
STIRLING:
Yes.

28:11.862 --> 28:13.090
BERK:
Now.

28:13.464 --> 28:16.331
Would you like me to free myself
from these?

28:16.500 --> 28:19.731
With brute force or with magic?

28:19.903 --> 28:21.928
- Magic.
CHILDREN: Magic.

28:22.106 --> 28:24.540
All right, then. All right, then.

28:25.242 --> 28:27.301
Let's count. See how long it takes.

28:27.478 --> 28:29.139
[INHALES DEEPLY]

28:29.446 --> 28:33.678
CHILDREN:
One, two, three...

28:33.851 --> 28:35.785
[ALL GASP]

28:35.953 --> 28:37.215
CHILDREN:
Wow.

28:39.423 --> 28:41.084
Wow!

28:41.625 --> 28:44.594
- How'd you do that?
- It's magic.

28:45.662 --> 28:49.598
KIT: <i>And, Dad, please remember,</i>
<i>I miss you more than you know.</i>

28:49.767 --> 28:53.533
<i>We all do. Never forget that.</i>

28:55.906 --> 28:57.533
Hi.

28:58.842 --> 28:59.866
Hi.

29:00.044 --> 29:01.568
[SNEEZES]

29:01.745 --> 29:02.803
[WHINES]

29:02.980 --> 29:04.311
Sorry.

29:04.748 --> 29:06.238
Allergies.

29:06.650 --> 29:08.413
These are from your room.

29:08.986 --> 29:11.318
Uh, just leave them there.

29:11.488 --> 29:13.353
I'll put them away.

29:20.330 --> 29:22.161
Is that...

29:22.933 --> 29:24.628
...Ernie Lombardi?

29:24.802 --> 29:26.201
Yep.

29:27.771 --> 29:29.636
STIRLING:
A picture of the Schnoz.

29:30.374 --> 29:33.639
Did you know
that he's the biggest player on the team?

29:33.811 --> 29:36.644
Six-foot-three, 230 pounds.

29:36.814 --> 29:38.076
He's my favorite.

29:38.248 --> 29:41.342
That's funny. He's got a huge nose
and you've got...

29:41.518 --> 29:43.008
Huge ears.

29:43.854 --> 29:45.412
- I know.
- Ha, ha.

29:45.589 --> 29:47.523
That's why I like him.

29:49.093 --> 29:51.926
I'm sorry we put you out of your room.

29:52.229 --> 29:55.027
That's all right.
I can get more writing done here.

29:55.766 --> 29:58.326
- What do you write?
- News articles.

30:00.003 --> 30:02.699
- For your family?
- And for the <i>Cincinnati Register.</i>

30:03.173 --> 30:05.004
You write for the newspaper?

30:06.710 --> 30:10.544
Well, I haven't been in "print" print yet.
But I hope to be.

30:10.714 --> 30:13.945
My brother's friend is a big reporter
for the <i>Register.</i>

30:14.118 --> 30:16.052
Sorry, kiddo, not for the <i>Register.</i>

30:16.220 --> 30:18.984
But everyone wants to know
about the Chicago World's Fair.

30:19.156 --> 30:23.490
Everyone and their second cousin's written
about the Chicago World's Fair.

30:25.195 --> 30:27.993
- You know what Mr. Gibson says?
- Yeah, yeah, do it.

30:34.371 --> 30:36.168
[CLEARS THROAT]

30:36.707 --> 30:38.971
[AS GIBSON] I want something new.
I want something fresh.

30:39.143 --> 30:41.976
I want something real.
Don't sugarcoat your stories, boys.

30:42.146 --> 30:45.673
This is the <i>Cincinnati Register,</i>
a beacon of cold, clear light...

30:45.849 --> 30:48.943
...in a sea of sentimental flop.

30:49.887 --> 30:52.583
So, what were you saying, Mr?

30:52.756 --> 30:56.852
Uh, Peabody.
Sir, uh, William Peabody and nothing.

30:57.060 --> 30:59.494
- I was just quoting you, sir.
- Oh.

31:00.097 --> 31:02.327
Wait, Mr. Gibson.

31:02.599 --> 31:03.896
Well.

31:04.935 --> 31:07.096
Hello, sweetie, what's your name?

31:07.304 --> 31:09.829
Kit Kittredge.
Well, actually, it's Margaret Mildred...

31:10.007 --> 31:14.034
...after my mother and an aunt. But when
I was younger, my father used to sing:

31:14.211 --> 31:18.113
[SINGING]
<i>Pack up your troubles in your old kit bag</i>

31:18.649 --> 31:19.877
And it sort of stuck.

31:21.084 --> 31:22.210
Sir.

31:22.386 --> 31:24.411
- Fascinating.
- Wait.

31:26.523 --> 31:29.185
I wrote an article
I think you should publish.

31:29.359 --> 31:30.348
Oh.

31:30.527 --> 31:33.360
Well, thank you very much.

31:34.097 --> 31:37.123
And, by the way, I don't lisp.

31:37.401 --> 31:41.303
[RENEE OLSTEAD'S "AIN'T WE
GOT FUN" PLAYING ON GRAMOPHONE]

31:55.385 --> 31:56.409
[ENGINE SPUTTERING]

31:56.587 --> 31:58.851
[HORN HONKING]

32:03.894 --> 32:05.623
[ENGINE BACKFIRES]

32:05.796 --> 32:08.458
Whoopsy daisy.

32:10.567 --> 32:13.092
Whoo! Are you all right?

32:13.270 --> 32:15.465
Uh, yeah, as long as that horn works.

32:15.639 --> 32:18.164
Ha, ha. Now, can I interest you in a book?

32:20.477 --> 32:24.072
- I don't have much time for reading.
- Well, you should take the time to read.

32:24.248 --> 32:28.184
It's a wonderful way
to go wherever you want.

32:28.352 --> 32:32.186
I've just finished reading this one.

32:33.290 --> 32:34.655
<i>The Adventures of Robin Hood?</i>

32:34.825 --> 32:37.726
He steals from the rich,
and then he gives to the poor.

32:37.894 --> 32:40.795
COUNTEE: And then what happened to him?
- Well, he'll have to tell you.

32:40.964 --> 32:43.091
What about you, Countee?
Would you like one?

32:43.367 --> 32:44.925
I can only read Hobo.

32:45.736 --> 32:48.000
Oh, I've never tried that. Hmm.

32:48.171 --> 32:51.299
How about I teach you to read books,
and you teach me to read Hobo?

32:51.475 --> 32:52.942
That'd be swell, Stirling.

32:54.778 --> 32:55.938
How about this one?

32:56.513 --> 32:58.140
Thank you.

33:01.051 --> 33:04.077
- It's a loaner, though.
- Okay.

33:08.925 --> 33:10.017
Will?

33:11.328 --> 33:12.454
[GASPS]

33:12.629 --> 33:14.358
- Are you okay?
- Ha, ha.

33:15.232 --> 33:16.665
Will?

33:19.002 --> 33:21.835
I want you to have
Mr. Kittredge's old boots.

33:22.706 --> 33:23.968
No, ma'am, I couldn't.

33:24.141 --> 33:27.201
You've done wonderful work.
Beyond what you and Countee have eaten.

33:27.377 --> 33:30.869
I insist you take these
before those things fall off your feet.

33:33.283 --> 33:34.750
Thank you.

33:35.085 --> 33:36.484
Go on.

33:38.989 --> 33:41.457
- Miss Bond.
- Mrs. Kittredge.

33:41.625 --> 33:43.217
Will.

33:44.461 --> 33:46.224
Ruthie.

33:48.398 --> 33:50.593
Hi, Ruthie. What's wrong?

33:50.767 --> 33:53.668
- Morning.
- We're going on vacation.

33:53.837 --> 33:57.398
Myrtle Beach, 10 days, starting Friday.

33:57.574 --> 34:01.237
- And that's bad because...?
RUTHIE: It's so much more fun here.

34:01.411 --> 34:04.346
You're all I ever talk about at home.
Even ask my mom.

34:04.514 --> 34:06.709
The other day,
I was telling her about you, Miss Dooley.

34:06.883 --> 34:08.510
Aw, thank you.

34:08.685 --> 34:11.245
She didn't say
what she was saying about you.

34:13.523 --> 34:17.289
You know what you need? A novelette.

34:17.994 --> 34:19.393
What are you writing?

34:19.563 --> 34:22.088
You just gave me a great idea
for an article.

34:22.264 --> 34:24.859
I wanna write it down before I forget.

34:25.168 --> 34:26.533
Here.

34:27.270 --> 34:30.433
I'll do this for you, and you go type it up
before you forget, okay?

34:31.308 --> 34:33.572
- Are you sure?
- Go.

34:34.210 --> 34:36.610
KIT: Thanks, Ruthie.
- I have just the thing.

34:39.783 --> 34:41.751
WILL:
They fit real good.

34:42.686 --> 34:44.244
Thank you.

34:47.090 --> 34:48.717
Pretty.

34:54.931 --> 34:56.831
Wish me luck.

34:59.736 --> 35:01.169
GIBSON:
Who is it?

35:01.338 --> 35:03.135
Margaret Mildred Kittredge.

35:04.541 --> 35:07.066
- What do you want?
- To be in print.

35:07.544 --> 35:10.274
Well, how do I say this nicely?

35:10.447 --> 35:12.244
[GASPS]

35:15.318 --> 35:18.549
- But you haven't even read it!
- She's sorry, Mr. Gibson.

35:18.722 --> 35:21.020
- Come on, Kit.
- Yeah, that's right, I am sorry.

35:21.191 --> 35:26.254
I'm sorry you can't recognize a good story
when it's standing right outside your door.

35:26.730 --> 35:27.992
What did you say?

35:29.933 --> 35:34.063
Portrait of a boarding house, sir.
It's fresh. It's new. It's real.

35:34.237 --> 35:38.640
What you're holding in your hand, sir,
is the story you've been looking for.

35:38.809 --> 35:42.677
And you can throw me out if you want,
but I suggest that you read it first.

35:43.079 --> 35:45.547
"A Kid's-Eye View of the Depression
in Cincinnati."

35:45.715 --> 35:47.842
By Kit Kittredge, age 10.

35:48.018 --> 35:50.418
STAFF: Ha, ha.
GIBSON: That's enough.

35:56.660 --> 35:58.719
[SIGHS]

36:14.344 --> 36:15.368
You wrote this?

36:16.112 --> 36:17.511
Yes.

36:18.849 --> 36:19.873
It's not bad.

36:21.418 --> 36:25.286
KIT: Are you going to print it, Mr. Gibson?
- I'm sorry, kid.

36:25.789 --> 36:27.984
"Not bad" is good...

36:28.158 --> 36:29.819
...but it's not good enough.

36:31.995 --> 36:35.931
Keep it up, kid.
We pay a penny a word for freelance.

36:36.466 --> 36:40.368
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven, eight.

36:41.171 --> 36:43.969
And guess what.
They pay a penny a word.

36:44.140 --> 36:47.371
Which means, I can make two
or three dollars from just one article.

36:47.544 --> 36:49.876
Whoo-ee!

36:50.046 --> 36:53.914
I was thinking about doing a story
on you and Countee, Will, if you let me.

36:54.150 --> 36:55.708
What's so interesting about us?

36:55.886 --> 36:58.719
I'd like to find out,
shadow you for the day.

36:58.889 --> 37:02.086
- That's reporter talk.
- Oh, yeah.

37:02.259 --> 37:05.786
Well, actually, I'm on my way out
to get a few things...

37:05.962 --> 37:07.259
...at my camp.

37:07.797 --> 37:09.264
You can come if you'd like.

37:10.567 --> 37:12.899
Unless you need us here, Mother.

37:13.136 --> 37:14.694
No, I can manage.

37:15.338 --> 37:17.033
Come on, Countee.

37:23.079 --> 37:26.105
Ruthie, Stirling.
Would you like to be my assistants?

37:26.550 --> 37:28.415
- Do we get paid?
- No.

37:28.718 --> 37:30.811
- Okay.
RUTHIE: Yeah.

37:31.421 --> 37:35.118
KIT: Will, Countee was saying something
about reading Hobo signs?

37:35.292 --> 37:38.284
You know, he can read a sign
on a gatepost about 200 yards out.

37:38.461 --> 37:42.591
- He's saved my hide about a hundred times.
- What kind of sign's on a gatepost?

37:42.766 --> 37:44.893
The ones that hobos leave
to help each other.

37:46.102 --> 37:48.400
- You see that?
- Looks like a cat.

37:48.572 --> 37:51.166
It is a cat. It's a good sign too.

37:51.608 --> 37:53.872
It means a kind lady lives here.

37:54.411 --> 37:58.074
- Not many houses want hobos, you know.
- You had a cat on your gate, Kit.

37:58.815 --> 38:03.081
- We had a cat.
- Well, I live over there. Do I have a cat?

38:03.253 --> 38:06.279
- Oh, I hope we have a cat.
- I'm sure you have a cat.

38:09.159 --> 38:10.649
Sorry, Ruthie. No cat.

38:11.494 --> 38:13.655
But you do have fish bones, see?

38:14.564 --> 38:18.193
- Oh, what's that mean?
- Good garbage.

38:23.306 --> 38:26.139
KIT:
So, what's it like riding the rails, Will?

38:26.309 --> 38:28.038
WILL:
Train whistles.

38:28.211 --> 38:31.647
Engines smokes up,
and you run and you jump.

38:32.082 --> 38:34.812
And you let it take you
to a whole new life.

38:35.452 --> 38:38.512
- Makes a man feel free. Right, Countee?
- That's right.

38:39.255 --> 38:41.120
So where's home, Will?

38:41.291 --> 38:43.122
Uh...

38:43.293 --> 38:45.056
Texas.

38:45.362 --> 38:48.422
We had a farm.
Crops failed two years in a row.

38:48.598 --> 38:50.793
Daddy fought to keep it,
but when he couldn't...

38:50.967 --> 38:54.494
...they headed out west with Belle
and Evelyn and my younger sisters.

38:54.671 --> 38:56.434
They wanted me to go too...

38:56.606 --> 38:59.473
...but I figured it was time for me
to strike out on my own...

38:59.643 --> 39:03.977
...so I rode the rails, uh, made a few friends
and worked when I could.

39:04.481 --> 39:09.180
That's when I met Countee and his father
in Oklahoma about 14 months ago.

39:09.352 --> 39:11.582
Kind of stuck together after that.

39:11.755 --> 39:14.383
- Called ourselves...
- "The Three Musketeers."

39:15.325 --> 39:17.919
- Ha, ha.
- Yes, we did.

39:21.464 --> 39:22.590
And, um...

39:25.201 --> 39:27.362
And then the influenza came.

39:28.271 --> 39:30.671
And my daddy didn't make it.

39:34.344 --> 39:36.209
Now it's just us.

39:37.313 --> 39:39.008
Thank the good Lord I've got him.

39:39.349 --> 39:42.876
Soon we're gonna make it out to California
and meet the rest of the family.

39:43.053 --> 39:44.611
Are they gonna like me?

39:47.190 --> 39:48.657
No.

39:51.161 --> 39:54.562
I'm just playing. Come on, let's go.

39:55.699 --> 39:56.859
Let's get going.

40:00.036 --> 40:01.264
You know what that means?

40:01.871 --> 40:03.338
KIT:
Does it mean we're close?

40:03.506 --> 40:05.497
COUNTEE:
That means we're near a hobo jungle.

40:05.675 --> 40:07.472
RUTHIE:
What is a hobo, exactly?

40:07.644 --> 40:10.875
WILL: A person who hops the rails,
going from town to town looking for work.

40:11.981 --> 40:13.471
Like a lot of these folks right here.

40:13.650 --> 40:16.346
[TRAIN WHISTLES IN DISTANCE]

40:16.519 --> 40:19.454
Here it is. Home sweet home.

40:20.123 --> 40:21.249
Come on.

40:25.695 --> 40:28.425
KIT:
<i>Life inside a hobo jungle sure isn't easy.</i>

40:28.598 --> 40:31.624
<i>These people once had houses and jobs.</i>

40:31.801 --> 40:34.361
<i>I guess we're all just a few strokes</i>
<i>of bad luck away...</i>

40:34.537 --> 40:36.368
<i>... from being in that exact same spot.</i>

40:36.539 --> 40:37.563
WILL:
Eddie, down there.

40:37.741 --> 40:39.572
KIT:
<i>Every day's a challenge for food.</i>

40:39.743 --> 40:42.177
<i>In most camps,</i>
<i>hobos share what they have:</i>

40:42.345 --> 40:46.338
<i>Vegetables, potatoes</i>
<i>and, on a good day, maybe meat.</i>

40:46.516 --> 40:48.780
KIT: Would you mind if I took
a couple pictures of you?

40:48.952 --> 40:50.283
MAN:
Of course you can.

40:50.453 --> 40:54.753
KIT: <i>They put it in a pot and cook it</i>
<i>all together and call it hobo stew.</i>

40:54.924 --> 40:57.256
- <i>Those that can contribute do.</i>
WILL: Did you get meat?

40:57.427 --> 41:00.692
KIT: <i>Those that can't</i>
<i>try harder the next day.</i>

41:00.864 --> 41:03.264
<i>But everyone's welcome to share.</i>

41:04.234 --> 41:05.792
<i>They even have a hobo store...</i>

41:05.969 --> 41:09.029
<i>... where you leave what you don't want</i>
<i>and take what you do.</i>

41:11.508 --> 41:15.274
<i>For the most part, they seem like</i>
<i>a trustworthy group of people.</i>

41:15.445 --> 41:18.312
<i>But trouble must follow them a lot.</i>

41:18.481 --> 41:21.678
<i>The first sign a hobo learns is danger.</i>

41:24.921 --> 41:27.048
<i>They needed to protect themselves...</i>

41:27.223 --> 41:29.157
<i>... and each other.</i>

41:30.326 --> 41:33.318
<i>When times are tough,</i>
<i>people like to blame someone.</i>

41:34.764 --> 41:36.994
<i>And hobos are an easy target, I guess.</i>

41:37.167 --> 41:39.226
[CAMERA CLICKING]

41:42.372 --> 41:43.805
Here we are.

41:46.042 --> 41:47.100
Bedroom.

41:47.277 --> 41:49.837
Uh, lounge.

41:50.013 --> 41:51.037
Bathroom.

41:51.214 --> 41:52.841
[ALL LAUGH]

41:53.550 --> 41:56.212
- Library.
COUNTEE: Come on in.

41:56.786 --> 41:58.845
KIT: You actually sleep here?
- Hi, doc.

41:59.022 --> 42:00.284
Will.

42:00.456 --> 42:02.287
How's that throat of Countee's?

42:02.458 --> 42:05.552
- Oh, it's doing much better. Thank you.
- Good.

42:05.728 --> 42:07.252
Robin Hood, huh?

42:07.764 --> 42:08.890
Yeah.

42:09.065 --> 42:11.499
Hey, uh...
Doc, what do you think about a person...

42:11.668 --> 42:14.603
...who steals from the rich
and gives to the poor?

42:15.071 --> 42:17.835
Is he a good guy or a bad guy?

42:19.809 --> 42:21.572
I'd have to say a good one.

42:23.346 --> 42:24.870
Yeah, me too.

42:26.015 --> 42:27.539
See you, doc.

42:28.284 --> 42:29.615
Will.

42:30.186 --> 42:33.053
Hey. Y'all come out here.
I got someone to introduce you to.

42:33.223 --> 42:34.622
KIT: Okay.
RUTHIE: Okay.

42:34.791 --> 42:36.383
PENNINGTON:
Welcome.

42:38.127 --> 42:40.925
Sheldon Pennington III.

42:42.298 --> 42:46.826
- Stirling Howard IV.
- Kit Kittredge I.

42:47.070 --> 42:48.298
I'm Ruthie.

42:48.471 --> 42:50.701
- We're friends of Will and Countee.
- Ah.

42:50.874 --> 42:54.310
Pennington's the name,
stocks and bonds were my game.

42:55.445 --> 42:57.310
My father used to be in stocks too.

42:57.480 --> 43:00.711
Ah. Operative words, "used to be."

43:00.884 --> 43:05.583
You'll find a lot of men around here
who used to be one thing or another.

43:07.724 --> 43:09.954
When I acquire
some gainful employment...

43:10.126 --> 43:12.492
...I am going to send for my wife
and two sons.

43:12.662 --> 43:15.597
One of them is just about your age.

43:16.266 --> 43:17.631
LOUISE:
<i>Stirling Howard IV...</i>

43:17.934 --> 43:19.401
...where have you been?

43:19.769 --> 43:22.067
With Will and Countee
at the hobo jungle.

43:25.475 --> 43:28.069
Don't you ever take him there again,
do you understand?

43:28.244 --> 43:29.472
Ever.

43:29.979 --> 43:31.469
Yes, ma'am.

43:31.881 --> 43:34.645
It wasn't his fault. Uh, uh...

43:34.817 --> 43:37.843
- I was just...
- I gave them permission, Louise.

43:38.688 --> 43:40.315
Excuse us.

43:40.657 --> 43:42.682
I warned you about spending time
with those hobos.

43:42.859 --> 43:45.089
STIRLING: Mom...
LOUISE: A lot of them are criminals.

43:45.261 --> 43:48.492
- Next time, you get permission from me.
- I have to go.

43:48.998 --> 43:50.295
Come on.

43:50.466 --> 43:56.371
KIT: Ah. I'm sorry, Mother.
- Oh, you don't have to apologize.

43:57.974 --> 44:00.738
We just can't afford
to antagonize the boarders, that's all.

44:00.910 --> 44:02.639
Here, sit with me.

44:05.815 --> 44:08.079
I never wanted this for you.

44:09.919 --> 44:11.546
Should be...

44:11.721 --> 44:16.988
...out playing, not worrying about boarders
and mortgages...

44:17.961 --> 44:19.053
...and selling eggs.

44:19.228 --> 44:20.354
Selling what?

44:20.530 --> 44:23.863
- Uh, eggs.
- But we don't have any chickens.

44:24.033 --> 44:26.934
Yes, we do. Aunt Millie sent them.

44:27.270 --> 44:28.999
Kit, it will help us.

44:31.607 --> 44:33.074
- Oh, no.
- Kit.

44:33.242 --> 44:34.869
- No.
- Kit.

44:35.044 --> 44:38.445
Everyone knows that selling eggs
is one step away from the poorhouse.

44:38.614 --> 44:39.911
Margaret Mildred, sit down.

44:42.385 --> 44:43.545
Look at me.

44:43.720 --> 44:47.156
Selling eggs, growing vegetables,
reusing everything we can...

44:47.323 --> 44:50.121
...may be the only thing
to keep us out of poorhouse.

44:50.293 --> 44:53.558
And it's either that
or go to live with Uncle Hendrick.

44:54.130 --> 44:56.564
Until your father finds work.

44:57.800 --> 44:59.267
So, what'll it be?

45:00.036 --> 45:01.560
The chickens or the uncle?

45:03.106 --> 45:04.903
Hmm?

45:05.408 --> 45:06.670
I'll take the chickens.

45:06.843 --> 45:08.777
[LAUGHS]

45:09.045 --> 45:10.672
Thank you, thank you.

45:10.847 --> 45:14.681
Thank you. Thank you.
I, Jefferson J. Berk...

45:14.851 --> 45:17.217
...will suspend a person in midair.

45:17.954 --> 45:19.216
Levitation?

45:19.389 --> 45:22.187
Mm-hm.
No trickery, no distractions.

45:22.525 --> 45:27.428
Right under your noses,
I will make someone in this room float.

45:29.032 --> 45:30.659
Weightless.

45:32.268 --> 45:33.565
I need a volunteer.

45:36.272 --> 45:38.035
Miss Bond?

45:39.242 --> 45:42.268
I have never levitated
a mobile librarian before.

45:42.745 --> 45:44.736
Have you ever levitated
a dance instructor?

45:45.181 --> 45:47.046
Yes, but that's a long story.

45:47.216 --> 45:48.911
- Come, Miss Bond.
- Oh, no.

45:49.085 --> 45:50.950
MISS DOOLEY: Yes.
- No, Mr. Berk, I couldn't.

45:51.120 --> 45:52.280
KIT: Yeah.
STIRLING: Come on.

45:52.455 --> 45:53.717
KIT: There you go.
- Yeah.

45:53.890 --> 45:56.586
CHILDREN:
Miss Bond, Miss Bond, Miss Bond.

45:57.927 --> 45:59.895
Oh!

46:00.063 --> 46:02.657
- All right, but it won't work.
BERK: Please sit down.

46:02.832 --> 46:04.925
MISS BOND: All right.
BERK: Lean back.

46:07.003 --> 46:09.938
MISS BOND: All right.
BERK: That's it, very good.

46:10.106 --> 46:13.940
Cross your arms over your chest.
Good. Close your eyes.

46:14.110 --> 46:17.204
Close your eyes. Close your eyes.

46:17.680 --> 46:19.307
- Are you comfortable?
- No.

46:19.482 --> 46:21.416
Excellent. Children, the lights, please?

46:23.786 --> 46:25.754
Miss Dooley, would you accompany me?

46:25.922 --> 46:27.321
I do.

46:27.490 --> 46:28.980
Will, yes.

46:32.862 --> 46:35.330
[MISS DOOLEY CLEARS THROAT]

46:37.800 --> 46:41.861
[PLAYING SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

46:47.977 --> 46:49.501
BERK:
Miss Bond.

46:49.679 --> 46:52.204
You are getting sleepy.

46:52.381 --> 46:54.372
Very sleepy.

46:54.550 --> 46:56.450
You're feeling as light as air.

46:56.619 --> 46:59.554
And you only hear my voice.
Only my voice.

46:59.722 --> 47:02.316
All other sounds fade away.

47:02.792 --> 47:07.229
Your eyelids are getting heavy, very heavy.
You can barely keep them open.

47:08.030 --> 47:09.622
You...

47:09.932 --> 47:11.661
...are now...

47:12.969 --> 47:13.993
...asleep.

47:15.238 --> 47:17.229
- Ah!
- Shh.

47:17.406 --> 47:20.204
[WHISPERING] Please, Mrs. Howard,
any loud noise could awaken her...

47:20.376 --> 47:21.968
...and she could fall.

47:44.333 --> 47:46.062
[CREAK]

47:55.778 --> 47:57.245
Shh!

48:11.260 --> 48:12.955
[CREAK]

48:59.475 --> 49:00.908
[SNAPS]

49:08.918 --> 49:11.284
[CHILDREN LAUGHING]

49:11.454 --> 49:12.478
CHILDREN:
Yeah, yeah.

49:12.655 --> 49:14.680
Miss Bond, ladies and gentlemen.

49:16.259 --> 49:18.250
Well, I told you it wouldn't work.

49:21.230 --> 49:26.133
Mother, Mother, you should have seen it.
Mr. Berk just levitated Miss Bond.

49:26.769 --> 49:29.101
Well, are you all right?

49:29.272 --> 49:31.763
Of course I am
because nothing happened.

49:31.941 --> 49:33.533
- Yes, it did.
- Oh, no.

49:33.709 --> 49:34.971
- You were in the air.
- No.

49:35.144 --> 49:36.543
- Is that the mail?
- Yes.

49:36.712 --> 49:40.170
- Uh, excuse me for a moment.
- Uh, but the mail's here, Mother.

49:40.349 --> 49:42.544
- Mr. Berk.
- Thank you.

49:42.718 --> 49:43.946
- Miss Bond.
- Ooh!

49:44.120 --> 49:46.554
- Is there one from Dad?
- No, sweetie, not today.

49:47.256 --> 49:49.224
Aw. He writes often enough.

49:49.392 --> 49:52.884
I must say, Mrs. K., if I marry,
when I marry...

49:53.062 --> 49:55.587
...I hope my husband
is half as attentive as yours.

49:55.765 --> 49:58.700
My luck, I'll probably get some deadbeat
who never...

49:59.235 --> 50:01.726
Mind. Never mind.

50:01.904 --> 50:05.362
- Oh, no. Oh, no.
- Is anything wrong?

50:05.741 --> 50:10.576
Oh, my poor cousin Frederich,
he was jumped by a hobo.

50:11.080 --> 50:13.378
Took his watch, his wallet...

50:13.549 --> 50:14.880
...and beat him pretty badly.

50:15.051 --> 50:16.712
- Oh.
MISS DOOLEY: What a shame.

50:16.886 --> 50:18.376
Is his wife looking after him?

50:19.989 --> 50:21.854
- No, he's not married.
- Oh.

50:22.024 --> 50:24.584
BERK:
In fact, I'm the only family he has.

50:24.760 --> 50:28.321
Mrs. Kittredge, would you mind if he came
and stayed with us for a few days?

50:28.497 --> 50:32.627
I mean, when he gets better.
I promise, I will pay extra for his meals.

50:32.802 --> 50:35.396
Of course, I have a spare cot in the attic.

50:35.571 --> 50:37.596
- I'll get it ready for you.
- Thank you.

50:37.773 --> 50:40.537
Miss Bond and I were just talking
about these hobo crimes.

50:40.710 --> 50:44.544
Well, it's gossip, really.
You hear these things when you're mobile.

50:44.714 --> 50:49.242
But they say
there's been a slew of hobo robberies.

50:49.418 --> 50:53.855
- Well, not all hobos are alike.
- They've been ransacking people's homes...

50:54.023 --> 50:57.481
...and mugging them in broad daylight.
Really, something should be done.

50:57.660 --> 50:59.924
Well, there's talk of running them
out of town.

51:00.930 --> 51:02.693
BERK:
They are ransacking people's homes.

51:02.865 --> 51:05.732
I wonder if it's not a bad idea
if we don't lock up our valuables.

51:05.901 --> 51:07.994
I sew my money into my unmentionables.

51:08.170 --> 51:10.638
Oh, Miss Dooley,
please, there are children here.

51:10.806 --> 51:13.366
Don't they wear unmentionables?
I certainly hope so.

51:13.542 --> 51:14.941
[CHILDREN GIGGLE]

51:15.111 --> 51:17.375
My father keeps our money
in the basement safe.

51:17.546 --> 51:21.744
Ha! Isn't that a kicker?
The banker who doesn't trust the bank.

51:21.917 --> 51:25.717
Mrs. K., would you mind keeping that
in your lockbox?

51:25.888 --> 51:28.288
It's old and, they say, quite valuable.

51:28.858 --> 51:30.553
Just in case.

51:30.893 --> 51:32.656
Of course. It's beautiful.

51:32.828 --> 51:34.796
Uh, yes?

51:34.964 --> 51:36.329
[CLEARS THROAT]

51:36.499 --> 51:39.093
Just wanna tell Ms. Kittredge
I found a place to put that coop...

51:39.268 --> 51:41.964
...over in the north corner
by the, uh, clothesline there.

51:42.138 --> 51:44.971
MARGARET: Excellent. Thank you, Will.
- Come on, Countee.

51:46.609 --> 51:47.633
Good day.

51:47.810 --> 51:49.573
- Bye, Will. Bye, Countee.
- Bye.

51:49.745 --> 51:52.111
I think perhaps I should lock these up
as well.

51:52.281 --> 51:54.772
Yes, I think I might follow suit.

51:54.950 --> 51:58.647
I should hate to lose my father's watch.

52:01.924 --> 52:04.188
LOUISE:
And these rings as well.

52:06.529 --> 52:08.520
But that's your wedding ring.

52:08.697 --> 52:12.895
LOUISE: It's okay.
It's just for safekeeping, Stirling.

52:15.871 --> 52:19.602
GIBSON: "Kindness and Honor
in the Hobo Community"?

52:20.443 --> 52:23.503
There's no question mark.
It's a declaration.

52:23.679 --> 52:26.443
"Kindness and Honor
in the Hobo Community."

52:26.615 --> 52:28.981
You've got to admit, it's fresh.

52:29.151 --> 52:30.880
Yes, but the thing is, sweetheart...

52:31.187 --> 52:36.716
...you generally want people
to buy the newspaper, not laugh at it.

52:36.892 --> 52:39.156
There are good hobos and bad ones, sir.

52:39.528 --> 52:41.462
Just like with apples.

52:41.864 --> 52:43.456
And with...

52:43.933 --> 52:45.025
...editors.

52:45.201 --> 52:46.896
[CHUCKLES]

52:47.069 --> 52:48.696
BILLY:
Come here, Kit.

52:49.805 --> 52:51.397
See that map?

52:53.042 --> 52:56.341
Every one of those cities,
Dayton, Hamilton, Cincinnati...

52:56.512 --> 52:59.504
...has reported crimes
where hobos are the prime suspects.

52:59.682 --> 53:03.140
They're offering $ 150
to anyone who catches the hobo criminals.

53:03.319 --> 53:07.688
So ask yourself, who's gonna pay a nickel
to hear what good folks hobos are?

53:08.090 --> 53:10.581
That's exactly why
they should hear it now.

53:10.759 --> 53:12.158
Let me give you a tip.

53:12.328 --> 53:15.764
Sometimes you gotta play the tune
your audience wants to sing to, Kit.

53:16.899 --> 53:19.424
There's been a burglary.
51 North Abbott Place.

53:20.102 --> 53:24.368
- Got an ID on a hobo with a limp.
- That's where Ruthie lives.

53:24.540 --> 53:26.405
[TIRES SCREECH]

53:30.045 --> 53:31.603
[CAR HORN HONKS]

53:34.083 --> 53:36.779
[CROWD CHATTERING]

53:42.424 --> 53:44.790
It was a hobo.
Jumped right out in front of me.

53:44.960 --> 53:46.257
Right out in broad daylight.

53:46.428 --> 53:48.055
- Had a limp too.
MAN: Yes.

53:48.230 --> 53:50.562
- Anything else?
- Did he have a tattoo?

53:50.733 --> 53:52.860
Something unusual, like a bird, maybe?

53:53.035 --> 53:56.801
- Okay, this is a crime scene, miss.
- Yeah, actually, he did have something.

53:56.972 --> 53:59.372
- Uh, bright colors.
- That's it.

53:59.542 --> 54:02.033
- That's the tattoo.
SHERIFF: Frank?

54:02.211 --> 54:03.269
Over here.

54:09.285 --> 54:14.120
- What do you make of that, sheriff?
SHERIFF: That I'd say is a calling card.

54:16.358 --> 54:17.450
KIT:
<i>Will?</i>

54:17.960 --> 54:19.860
Will?

54:22.698 --> 54:25.258
- Everything all right, Kit?
- Where's Will?

54:25.834 --> 54:27.961
I don't know.
He was supposed to be here.

54:28.370 --> 54:30.099
Maybe he got held up.

54:30.272 --> 54:31.398
Mail call.

54:31.574 --> 54:34.008
Ah. If it was only that easy.

54:34.176 --> 54:39.136
Let's see, we have one for Mr. Berk.
I'll give that to him later.

54:39.548 --> 54:40.913
Of course, Mrs. Kittredge.

54:42.718 --> 54:44.345
From Dad?

54:46.655 --> 54:49.146
Uh, it's from Aunt Millie.

54:49.325 --> 54:51.088
And, Stirling, there's one for you.

54:53.862 --> 54:55.227
STIRLING:
Mother.

54:55.397 --> 54:56.830
It's from New York.

54:57.366 --> 54:58.663
From Dad.

55:04.106 --> 55:06.700
And there's one in here for you too.

55:07.409 --> 55:09.070
[SIGHS]

55:14.717 --> 55:15.706
[GASPS]

55:16.518 --> 55:18.110
Forty dollars?

55:20.656 --> 55:22.521
Um...

55:23.692 --> 55:25.319
Excuse me.

55:30.599 --> 55:32.123
[DOOR CLOSES]

55:40.776 --> 55:42.767
[FOOTSTEPS CLIMBING STAIRS]

55:44.613 --> 55:45.841
KIT:
There you are.

55:46.015 --> 55:47.277
What are you doing up here?

55:47.449 --> 55:50.043
- Sorry, I was just...
- No, no, it's fine.

55:50.219 --> 55:52.687
I'm just changing the sheets.

55:55.257 --> 55:58.522
I was looking for you earlier.
I forgot to ask you about the letter.

55:58.694 --> 56:01.822
Does your father say
when he's coming back to Cincinnati?

56:05.934 --> 56:07.265
Stirling?

56:12.841 --> 56:14.001
Oh, no.

56:14.476 --> 56:17.274
He wants you to move to New York,
doesn't he?

56:19.882 --> 56:22.783
That's it. That's why you're so upset.

56:24.520 --> 56:26.750
Your father found a job in New York...

56:26.922 --> 56:29.254
...and now he wants you to move
with him.

56:30.259 --> 56:33.194
Why can't people find jobs in Cincinnati?

56:34.630 --> 56:36.791
I hate the mailman.

56:36.965 --> 56:38.557
And mailing...

56:38.734 --> 56:40.793
...letters and words. I hate words.

56:40.969 --> 56:44.530
- What are you talking about?
- Because you believe them.

56:45.107 --> 56:46.938
Even when they're not true.

56:52.014 --> 56:55.142
He said he'd write.
He said, "You'll hear from me."

56:55.984 --> 56:57.781
Your father?

56:57.986 --> 56:59.851
I made him promise.

57:00.222 --> 57:01.746
You did?

57:02.224 --> 57:03.987
He kept his word at first.

57:04.860 --> 57:07.158
I got a letter every week.

57:08.764 --> 57:11.392
Then they got fewer and fewer...

57:11.567 --> 57:14.195
...until one day, they just stopped.

57:16.905 --> 57:18.896
And then she took her ring off.

57:23.679 --> 57:26.307
You wrote that letter to your mother?

57:28.484 --> 57:30.782
She just needs to hear from him.

57:32.588 --> 57:34.818
But there was money inside.

57:38.794 --> 57:41.592
He gave it to me before he left.

57:43.398 --> 57:45.457
For an emergency.

57:48.437 --> 57:51.270
I think I always sort of knew.

57:54.543 --> 57:57.103
He's never coming back to us.

58:51.400 --> 58:53.061
[KIT SIGHS]

58:58.440 --> 59:00.067
Hi, Kit.

59:01.410 --> 59:03.708
I got something for you.

59:12.721 --> 59:14.416
It's a scooter.

59:15.757 --> 59:16.781
Thank you.

59:17.793 --> 59:20.318
Will, what happened to your leg?

59:20.495 --> 59:21.792
I hurt it the other night.

59:21.964 --> 59:25.024
Are you sure it didn't happen
yesterday morning?

59:28.537 --> 59:31.028
Do you mind
if I ask you a few questions, son?

59:31.206 --> 59:32.696
WILL:
No, sir.

59:35.811 --> 59:38.871
How exactly did you hurt your leg?

59:40.282 --> 59:41.306
I was jumped.

59:41.950 --> 59:43.747
SHERIFF:
Is that so?

59:44.586 --> 59:45.985
Yes, sir.

59:46.154 --> 59:47.951
It was the other night.

59:48.123 --> 59:50.114
Someone jumped me
and kicked me in the knee.

59:51.727 --> 59:53.922
Are those the boots you were wearing?

59:56.865 --> 01:00:00.562
- No, he took my boots.
- Now, isn't that a shame?

01:00:00.903 --> 01:00:04.304
Now, if we wanted to identify a footprint,
we'd be hard-pressed.

01:00:06.708 --> 01:00:09.142
Did you remember to report it?

01:00:10.545 --> 01:00:13.343
- Being a hobo, sir, who's gonna listen?
- Hmm.

01:00:14.149 --> 01:00:15.616
Do you know the Smithens?

01:00:17.452 --> 01:00:19.511
Ruthie Smithens?

01:00:20.956 --> 01:00:25.950
All these people seem to think
you know quite a bit about her.

01:00:26.762 --> 01:00:29.959
- About her financial situation.
- No. I don't know.

01:00:30.132 --> 01:00:33.158
Did you or did you not know
the Smithens were out of town?

01:00:35.837 --> 01:00:37.805
I knew they were gone, yes, sir.

01:00:37.973 --> 01:00:39.634
SHERIFF:
Do you remember her telling you...

01:00:39.808 --> 01:00:42.675
...they kept their money
in a safe in the basement?

01:00:44.246 --> 01:00:47.443
I'm gonna have to ask you
to remain local, son.

01:00:47.950 --> 01:00:51.078
You flip a train
in the middle of the night...

01:00:51.253 --> 01:00:54.279
...or you step one toe
outside the city limits...

01:00:54.456 --> 01:00:57.186
...I will track you down
and lock you up so fast...

01:00:57.359 --> 01:01:00.123
...you'll put those boots
right back on your feet.

01:01:00.295 --> 01:01:02.024
You understand me?

01:01:03.799 --> 01:01:05.630
[DOGS BARKING]

01:01:05.801 --> 01:01:06.859
BERK:
Stop! Thief!

01:01:07.703 --> 01:01:11.833
- Hey, you! Stop!
- Hello?

01:01:12.140 --> 01:01:14.040
Mother? Are you there?

01:01:14.209 --> 01:01:15.836
MARGARET: Kit? Stirling?
KIT: Who's there?

01:01:16.011 --> 01:01:19.139
- What's going on?
MARGARET: We've been robbed!

01:01:19.314 --> 01:01:21.544
One more time, Mr. Berk.

01:01:21.850 --> 01:01:23.317
I couldn't sleep.

01:01:23.485 --> 01:01:27.353
- I heard a noise, I thought, outside.
- So did I.

01:01:27.956 --> 01:01:31.016
So I went to check,
and that was when I saw him.

01:01:31.193 --> 01:01:32.387
Will Shepherd?

01:01:32.794 --> 01:01:33.852
It was dark.

01:01:34.663 --> 01:01:37.826
It was Will.
And he was carrying the lockbox.

01:01:39.434 --> 01:01:42.335
Ms. Kittredge, any of your belongings
in that lockbox?

01:01:43.171 --> 01:01:44.297
Um...

01:01:44.473 --> 01:01:46.668
...every penny we had
was in that lockbox.

01:01:47.209 --> 01:01:50.042
- He took your money?
- Of course he took their money.

01:01:50.212 --> 01:01:52.339
Knowing they needed it for the mortgage?

01:01:53.615 --> 01:01:55.742
- Let's pick him up, Frank.
- No.

01:01:58.387 --> 01:01:59.911
What a horrible boy.

01:02:01.256 --> 01:02:03.781
He talked a lot about Robin Hood, Kit.

01:02:03.959 --> 01:02:05.688
About stealing from the rich.

01:02:05.861 --> 01:02:09.262
But we're not rich, and he knows that.

01:02:09.431 --> 01:02:11.763
I don't believe it. I just don't believe it.

01:02:12.534 --> 01:02:16.561
FRANK: Will Shepherd?
Has anyone seen Will Shepherd?

01:02:17.272 --> 01:02:19.103
Will Shepherd?

01:02:31.153 --> 01:02:33.621
I'm sorry to bother you so early, ma'am.

01:02:33.922 --> 01:02:37.050
No, it's fine. Come in, please.

01:02:46.601 --> 01:02:48.899
- Morning.
- Morning.

01:02:49.671 --> 01:02:52.970
My deputy found these
in Will Shepherd's tent early this morning.

01:02:53.275 --> 01:02:55.505
We were hoping you could ID them for us,
ma'am.

01:02:57.479 --> 01:03:00.073
Are these the boots
you gave to Will Shepherd?

01:03:07.222 --> 01:03:08.553
And this?

01:03:09.024 --> 01:03:11.788
Oh, that's my brooch. Yes.

01:03:12.928 --> 01:03:15.761
Did...? Did you happen
to see my mother's ring?

01:03:16.364 --> 01:03:17.626
No, son.

01:03:17.799 --> 01:03:19.926
We figured he started
at the Smithens' house...

01:03:20.102 --> 01:03:22.730
...then moved on to yours.
It's an inside job, all right.

01:03:22.904 --> 01:03:24.201
No, it's impossible.

01:03:24.473 --> 01:03:26.998
The man who robbed the Smithens' house
had a tattoo.

01:03:27.175 --> 01:03:30.474
I heard it from an eyewitness.
I have notes.

01:03:30.645 --> 01:03:33.876
- Will doesn't have a tattoo, sheriff.
- Sweetheart.

01:03:34.049 --> 01:03:35.676
Have you found him yet?

01:03:36.718 --> 01:03:38.709
Nobody's seen him.

01:03:38.887 --> 01:03:41.685
Nobody seems to know where he is.

01:03:43.692 --> 01:03:45.557
KIT:
<i>Dear Dad, it's been weeks...</i>

01:03:45.727 --> 01:03:48.218
<i>... and there's still no sign</i>
<i>of Will or Countee.</i>

01:03:48.396 --> 01:03:50.421
<i>I just don't believe he'd rob us, Dad.</i>

01:03:50.599 --> 01:03:52.863
<i>But someone did,</i>
<i>and now our money's all gone.</i>

01:03:53.034 --> 01:03:57.368
<i>Now there's a foreclosure sign in the middle</i>
<i>of our beautiful, beautiful lawn.</i>

01:03:57.539 --> 01:04:01.236
<i>If that's not bad enough, Uncle Hendrick</i>
<i>said we can't bring Grace with us...</i>

01:04:01.409 --> 01:04:04.606
<i>... when we go to live with him.</i>
<i>We have to give her away, Dad.</i>

01:04:04.779 --> 01:04:07.009
<i>How can I give her away?</i>

01:04:07.182 --> 01:04:10.913
<i>I wanna ask Mother to talk to him again.</i>
<i>She's so sad, Dad.</i>

01:04:11.086 --> 01:04:13.350
<i>She hardly ever smiles.</i>

01:04:13.522 --> 01:04:15.012
<i>Dad, why aren't you here?</i>

01:04:15.190 --> 01:04:18.421
<i>Why haven't we heard from you?</i>
<i>You promised you'd write every week...</i>

01:04:18.593 --> 01:04:21.721
<i>... and now it just keeps getting</i>
<i>longer and longer between letters.</i>

01:04:21.897 --> 01:04:23.455
<i>You can't disappear.</i>

01:04:23.632 --> 01:04:26.294
<i>If you're not working in Chicago,</i>
<i>why can't you not work in Cin...?</i>

01:04:26.468 --> 01:04:27.526
[TYPEWRITER CLUNKS]

01:04:36.178 --> 01:04:37.702
[SIGHS]

01:04:43.385 --> 01:04:45.114
[SIGHS]

01:04:56.264 --> 01:04:57.754
[SIGHS]

01:04:58.266 --> 01:05:01.633
KIT: <i>Dear Dad, I got a letter</i>
<i>from Frances and Florence yesterday.</i>

01:05:01.803 --> 01:05:05.295
<i>They're settled with family</i>
<i>in Sacramento, California, doing great...</i>

01:05:05.473 --> 01:05:07.270
<i>... just like you said.</i>

01:05:07.442 --> 01:05:10.206
<i>Did Mother mention</i>
<i>that Ruthie's father spoke to the bank?</i>

01:05:10.378 --> 01:05:13.142
<i>And they're giving us an extra month</i>
<i>to stay in the house?</i>

01:05:13.315 --> 01:05:16.614
<i>I know that Ruthie pushed for us.</i>
<i>She's such a true friend.</i>

01:05:17.285 --> 01:05:20.743
<i>Last week, Mother made a dress for me</i>
<i>out of a chicken-feed sack.</i>

01:05:20.922 --> 01:05:23.322
<i>I wore it on the first day of school.</i>
<i>I didn't mind a bit.</i>

01:05:23.491 --> 01:05:24.617
GIRL:
It's so beautiful.

01:05:24.793 --> 01:05:27.694
KIT: <i>In fact, a few of the girls</i>
<i>thought it looked so smart...</i>

01:05:27.862 --> 01:05:30.797
<i>... she made some for them too.</i>
<i>For money.</i>

01:05:30.966 --> 01:05:32.228
<i>Imagine that.</i>

01:05:32.400 --> 01:05:34.800
<i>All that feed-sack material</i>
<i>was being thrown away.</i>

01:05:34.970 --> 01:05:36.369
<i>That's pure profit.</i>

01:05:36.538 --> 01:05:40.770
<i>Aunt Millie will be so proud,</i>
<i>and Uncle Hendrick will be horrified.</i>

01:05:40.942 --> 01:05:44.002
<i>I think I'll wear it the first day</i>
<i>we move in with him.</i>

01:05:45.180 --> 01:05:47.808
KIT: I know your legs are short,
but you can do it.

01:05:47.983 --> 01:05:49.450
Yes, good girl, good girl.

01:05:49.618 --> 01:05:53.349
KIT: <i>And selling eggs isn't as bad</i>
<i>as I thought. In fact, it's kind of fun.</i>

01:05:53.622 --> 01:05:58.286
Eggs! Get your eggs!
Fresh eggs. Fifteen cents a dozen.

01:05:58.460 --> 01:06:00.792
Get your eggs. Fresh eggs.

01:06:00.962 --> 01:06:04.489
KIT: <i>Mr. Berk went to pick up his cousin</i>
<i>Frederich from the train station.</i>

01:06:04.666 --> 01:06:07.157
<i>I think a new face in the house</i>
<i>will cheer us all up.</i>

01:06:07.335 --> 01:06:09.235
<i>And wherever Will and Countee</i>
<i>are, I only hope...</i>

01:06:09.404 --> 01:06:11.895
[CAR HORN HONKING]

01:06:16.978 --> 01:06:18.969
BERK:
Is he wearing the diaper?

01:06:19.147 --> 01:06:21.274
FREDERICH:
Yes, Jefferson.

01:06:22.350 --> 01:06:23.681
A monkey?

01:06:23.952 --> 01:06:25.783
[GIBBERING]

01:06:25.954 --> 01:06:27.615
[ALL LAUGHING]

01:06:27.989 --> 01:06:31.288
His name's Curtis. Hmm. Heh.

01:06:31.459 --> 01:06:33.120
[CLICKING TONGUE]

01:06:33.295 --> 01:06:37.959
I love you, Curtis.
Who's my little monkey boy?

01:06:38.133 --> 01:06:40.124
[CURTIS GIBBERING]

01:06:44.406 --> 01:06:46.340
[CHILDREN LAUGHING]

01:06:47.809 --> 01:06:49.640
He's so cute.

01:06:52.013 --> 01:06:53.037
[LOUISE GASPS]

01:06:53.214 --> 01:06:57.310
Stirling, get away
from that hideous creature now.

01:06:57.485 --> 01:06:58.884
Oh, oh, oh!

01:06:59.054 --> 01:07:00.988
Get it off. Get it off. Off, off, off!

01:07:02.324 --> 01:07:05.054
[LOUISE GROANING]

01:07:05.226 --> 01:07:06.818
Curtis, come.

01:07:08.296 --> 01:07:09.695
Scratch his little tummy...

01:07:10.065 --> 01:07:12.192
...and he'll be your friend forever,
won't you?

01:07:12.934 --> 01:07:14.401
If I scratch his...

01:07:14.803 --> 01:07:15.895
Margaret.

01:07:16.271 --> 01:07:19.729
It's a good thing we're moving
because otherwise, we'd move.

01:07:23.111 --> 01:07:26.774
Uh, Mr. Berk, there's a cot
ready for you upstairs now.

01:07:26.948 --> 01:07:30.213
I'm sorry for the mess.
It's such a large house to pack up.

01:07:30.385 --> 01:07:31.977
There's no time to do it.

01:07:32.153 --> 01:07:35.782
FREDERICH: Thanks for your trouble,
ma'am. I'm only staying a few days.

01:07:35.957 --> 01:07:39.222
- Are you from Baltimore too, Mr. Berk?
- Call me Frederich.

01:07:39.394 --> 01:07:40.383
[GIGGLES]

01:07:40.562 --> 01:07:43.395
FREDERICH: Originally, I'm from Canada.
- What a coincidence.

01:07:44.032 --> 01:07:46.865
- I thought you were from Poughkeepsie.
- Shh!

01:07:47.035 --> 01:07:50.903
Uh, but I moved to Baltimore in '22
to work with Jeff in the magic show.

01:07:51.072 --> 01:07:54.735
We called ourselves Luigi and Sam.

01:07:55.310 --> 01:07:57.210
I was Luigi.

01:07:57.612 --> 01:08:00.274
Yeah. Good times.

01:08:00.448 --> 01:08:01.745
Anyway.

01:08:01.916 --> 01:08:04.646
Jeff would saw a woman in half
while Lola sang.

01:08:05.019 --> 01:08:07.920
- Lola?
- Yeah.

01:08:09.023 --> 01:08:12.720
Lola. This was her favorite spot.

01:08:12.961 --> 01:08:15.486
May she rest in peace.

01:08:16.197 --> 01:08:18.926
KIT:
The sheriff said it was an inside job.

01:08:19.100 --> 01:08:21.591
So Mr. Berk knew
where Mother kept the jewels and money.

01:08:21.770 --> 01:08:25.796
But how did Mr. Berk get the brooch
out of the lockbox and into Will's tent?

01:08:25.974 --> 01:08:30.411
What if he never put the brooch
in the box?

01:08:30.578 --> 01:08:33.103
That's it. A sleight of hand.

01:08:33.281 --> 01:08:36.478
<i>Remember when Mr. Berk</i>
<i>put his watch in the jewelry bag?</i>

01:08:36.651 --> 01:08:39.916
<i>He must taken the brooch out,</i>
<i>put it in his pocket...</i>

01:08:40.087 --> 01:08:41.783
- And given it to...
- Frederich.

01:08:41.956 --> 01:08:43.856
He must have stolen Will's boots.

01:08:44.024 --> 01:08:47.961
Right. And that means that Frederich
must have gone to Will's camp...

01:08:48.129 --> 01:08:51.929
...dressed as a hobo
and hid the boots and jewelry in Will's tent.

01:08:52.567 --> 01:08:55.866
All Mr. Berk needed to do
was to make the sheriff suspect Will.

01:08:56.537 --> 01:08:57.970
The limp.

01:08:59.073 --> 01:09:01.234
Will said someone kicked him
in the knee.

01:09:01.408 --> 01:09:05.106
They made him limp
and then committed a crime...

01:09:05.279 --> 01:09:07.475
...where a limping hobo
could be identified.

01:09:08.082 --> 01:09:11.779
- At my house.
KIT: That's why he did it in broad daylight.

01:09:11.953 --> 01:09:13.818
<i>He left the boot print in the mud...</i>

01:09:14.255 --> 01:09:17.554
<i>... and wanted someone to see him</i>
<i>limp away.</i>

01:09:18.660 --> 01:09:19.921
MAN: What's going on over there?

01:09:20.094 --> 01:09:21.152
[DOG BARKING]

01:09:21.729 --> 01:09:24.630
We figured it out, Kit.
But now we have to go to the police.

01:09:24.799 --> 01:09:25.925
No, not without proof.

01:09:26.100 --> 01:09:27.260
[CAR DOOR CLOSES]

01:09:27.435 --> 01:09:29.403
BERK: Do you know where?
FREDERICH: Of course.

01:09:29.571 --> 01:09:30.629
BERK:
I certainly hope so.

01:09:30.805 --> 01:09:32.067
[ENGINE STARTS]

01:09:32.240 --> 01:09:33.298
KIT:
Perfect.

01:09:33.475 --> 01:09:36.069
Let's go look in their room for the money.

01:09:41.316 --> 01:09:43.341
If anyone comes back, blow this whistle.

01:09:43.852 --> 01:09:45.113
Are you sure about this?

01:09:45.286 --> 01:09:47.777
Look, how often is the house
completely empty?

01:09:47.956 --> 01:09:50.925
Everyone's gone. It's now or never.

01:09:54.963 --> 01:09:56.453
Come on.

01:10:05.173 --> 01:10:07.232
- Ruthie, keep watch.
- Okay.

01:10:14.315 --> 01:10:19.548
KIT: We need to find our money.
Where is it? It's all the money we have.

01:10:20.622 --> 01:10:21.816
In mystery novels...

01:10:21.990 --> 01:10:24.652
...there's usually a button
on the side of these trunks...

01:10:24.826 --> 01:10:26.794
...that opens a secret compartment.

01:10:26.961 --> 01:10:29.896
Where is it? Where's that button?

01:10:30.064 --> 01:10:31.861
[GRUNTING]

01:10:34.235 --> 01:10:35.463
Ruthie, I found it.

01:10:37.939 --> 01:10:39.463
[KIT GASPS]

01:10:39.641 --> 01:10:40.801
This is the red wallet.

01:10:42.677 --> 01:10:45.111
BERK: Thought you said you had a map.
FREDERICH: I do.

01:10:45.313 --> 01:10:46.644
I have one.

01:10:46.814 --> 01:10:49.408
- I just don't remember where exactly.
BERK: Oh, that's great.

01:10:49.584 --> 01:10:53.076
- You need a map to find the map, right?
- I've got a map, Jeff.

01:10:53.922 --> 01:10:55.321
[GASPS]

01:10:55.490 --> 01:10:58.220
Ruthie, your mother's necklace.

01:10:58.393 --> 01:11:00.122
But where's the lockbox?

01:11:02.997 --> 01:11:04.965
Look at this.

01:11:05.500 --> 01:11:09.095
Dayton. Cincinnati. Hamilton.

01:11:12.073 --> 01:11:13.734
Sarnia? No.

01:11:15.209 --> 01:11:16.471
Columbus.

01:11:16.878 --> 01:11:19.847
Cleveland. Ruthie, do you know
what this means?

01:11:20.181 --> 01:11:21.671
Yes.

01:11:21.849 --> 01:11:23.578
- No.
- Mr. Berk's cousin...

01:11:23.751 --> 01:11:26.447
...has been in every city
where the hobo crimes happened.

01:11:27.155 --> 01:11:30.090
Holy cow.

01:11:30.391 --> 01:11:32.552
Oh, my gosh. Where'd this come from?

01:11:32.727 --> 01:11:33.819
KIT:
Stirling.

01:11:34.295 --> 01:11:37.264
The hobo sign for danger.

01:11:39.867 --> 01:11:41.858
[CURTIS SCREECHING]

01:11:42.036 --> 01:11:43.663
FREDERICH:
Shh!

01:11:44.472 --> 01:11:46.633
[GROANS]

01:11:46.808 --> 01:11:49.777
Make him stop that squealing.
Put him in that thing.

01:11:51.679 --> 01:11:56.480
- He doesn't react well to tension.
- Neither do I. You don't hear me screaming!

01:11:56.751 --> 01:11:59.345
All right, just give me the map.
Come on, let's go.

01:12:00.355 --> 01:12:02.255
What are you doing?

01:12:05.660 --> 01:12:07.218
There is no map.

01:12:07.395 --> 01:12:11.491
Right? You buried the loot, but you have
no idea exactly where you buried it.

01:12:11.666 --> 01:12:14.226
Let me think, all right?

01:12:14.402 --> 01:12:17.462
- Just let me think.
- Yeah, well, that'll take forever.

01:12:17.639 --> 01:12:22.440
I put it somewhere I knew I wouldn't forget,
somewhere I was sure to find it.

01:12:25.913 --> 01:12:27.972
[LAUGHING]

01:12:29.283 --> 01:12:32.480
You see?
I'm not the numbskull you think I am.

01:12:32.654 --> 01:12:35.782
Okay, great. Let's just get going, okay?
Come on.

01:12:36.290 --> 01:12:38.417
Hey, what's this doing open?

01:12:38.593 --> 01:12:40.322
Is everything still there?

01:12:42.997 --> 01:12:45.227
- Where is it?
- Shh.

01:12:49.771 --> 01:12:52.865
You probably just left it open by accident.
Come on, let's go.

01:12:55.009 --> 01:12:57.068
Then what's this rock doing here?

01:12:57.445 --> 01:13:00.039
It probably came from the out-of-doors.

01:13:00.882 --> 01:13:05.216
It's got Hobo writing on it, Jefferson.
It means danger.

01:13:05.687 --> 01:13:07.211
I don't like it.

01:13:08.156 --> 01:13:09.453
Not one little bit.

01:13:11.025 --> 01:13:13.220
All right, help me with this trunk.

01:13:13.394 --> 01:13:16.363
- Where are we going with my trunk?
- No, we are not going anywhere.

01:13:16.531 --> 01:13:17.998
That would just raise suspicion.

01:13:18.166 --> 01:13:20.293
You are gonna tell me exactly
where the loot is buried.

01:13:20.468 --> 01:13:22.595
Then you're on a 4:00 train to Baltimore.

01:13:22.770 --> 01:13:25.762
Bal...? By...? By myself?

01:13:26.074 --> 01:13:27.769
I hate traveling alone.

01:13:28.643 --> 01:13:33.637
Frederich, if your instinct is right,
and I highly, highly doubt it...

01:13:34.315 --> 01:13:38.411
...I don't want to have any nosy boarders
or ambitious little sheriffs sniffing around.

01:13:38.586 --> 01:13:40.417
It's too risky. Do you understand me?

01:13:40.588 --> 01:13:42.715
- So let's go.
- What about Curtis?

01:13:43.925 --> 01:13:46.223
I promise I'll bring him to you
next week, okay?

01:13:46.394 --> 01:13:50.558
- You won't forget he likes raisins?
- Can we just go, please?!

01:13:52.333 --> 01:13:53.800
Come on.

01:13:56.037 --> 01:13:57.231
FREDERICH:
Wait, my coat.

01:14:00.108 --> 01:14:01.837
It's right there on the chair.

01:14:02.977 --> 01:14:04.444
Come on.

01:14:07.281 --> 01:14:10.114
BERK: Come on, you have everything now?
FREDERICH: Yeah.

01:14:18.192 --> 01:14:20.092
[SIGHS]

01:14:21.129 --> 01:14:23.324
It's okay. It's okay.

01:14:23.498 --> 01:14:24.760
[CURTIS SCREECHING]

01:14:24.932 --> 01:14:27.492
Shh! Good monkey. I'm getting in that car.

01:14:27.668 --> 01:14:28.999
What? Where are you going?

01:14:29.170 --> 01:14:31.968
- It's too dangerous. Stop.
- I need to get our money back.

01:14:32.140 --> 01:14:34.631
It's the only chance
we have to keep our home.

01:14:41.516 --> 01:14:43.711
RUTHIE:
Kit, no.

01:14:44.085 --> 01:14:45.575
Kit.

01:14:50.024 --> 01:14:52.219
Oh, my gosh. Kit, what are you doing?

01:14:57.665 --> 01:15:00.793
Stirling. Stirling, wake up. Are you okay?

01:15:00.968 --> 01:15:02.595
STIRLING:
Yeah.

01:15:03.204 --> 01:15:05.536
You and Ruthie get the police.
I'm going with them.

01:15:05.940 --> 01:15:07.430
What?

01:15:19.987 --> 01:15:21.716
[GASPS]

01:15:21.889 --> 01:15:23.720
[GROANS THEN THUDS]

01:15:24.258 --> 01:15:27.694
FREDERICH: Don't see why I gotta go.
BERK: Because you have to.

01:15:28.462 --> 01:15:30.589
Curtis.
You can't take a monkey on a train.

01:15:33.534 --> 01:15:36.230
[CURTIS SCREECHING]

01:15:37.205 --> 01:15:38.763
[GIBBERS]

01:15:38.940 --> 01:15:40.532
I love you too, Curtis.

01:15:41.375 --> 01:15:43.104
BERK:
Get in the car.

01:15:43.277 --> 01:15:44.505
[ENGINE STARTS]

01:15:45.279 --> 01:15:48.077
BERK: You know where everything is, right?
FREDERICH: Yeah, I know.

01:15:48.249 --> 01:15:49.409
- Yeah, I know.
BERK: Do you?

01:15:49.584 --> 01:15:51.313
Then where am I going?
Which way do I turn?

01:15:51.485 --> 01:15:53.453
FREDERICH: Left here.
BERK: Thanks for telling me.

01:15:53.621 --> 01:15:55.350
- That's nice.
FREDERICH: Stop yelling at me!

01:15:55.523 --> 01:15:59.516
BERK: I'm not. I'm trying to get information.
FREDERICH: I won't show you where.

01:15:59.694 --> 01:16:03.221
I know where it is, not you.
Who's smart now, Mr. Mustache-Bald-Head?

01:16:03.397 --> 01:16:05.092
BERK:
Moron!

01:16:07.268 --> 01:16:08.758
[HORN HONKS]

01:16:08.936 --> 01:16:11.302
[CRASH]

01:16:12.206 --> 01:16:13.730
RUTHIE: Miss Bond.
STERLING: Miss Bond.

01:16:13.908 --> 01:16:16.843
MISS BOND: What?
- Miss Bond. Stirling, come on.

01:16:17.011 --> 01:16:19.343
- Miss Bond, we need you.
- Miss Bond. Miss Bond.

01:16:19.513 --> 01:16:21.674
RUTHIE: We really need you.
- What?

01:16:21.849 --> 01:16:23.077
Really.

01:16:23.251 --> 01:16:25.412
We found out
that the Berks stole the money.

01:16:25.586 --> 01:16:27.918
And Kit got in the back of the car.

01:16:28.089 --> 01:16:30.683
And they said something
about a train station.

01:16:30.858 --> 01:16:32.849
Get in the car. Get in the car.

01:16:33.027 --> 01:16:35.154
RUTHIE: I'm going.
MISS BOND: I'll call the police.

01:16:44.538 --> 01:16:47.006
STERLING:
Whoa!

01:16:50.011 --> 01:16:53.640
BOTH: Whoa!
MISS BOND: Are you all right back there?

01:16:55.850 --> 01:16:58.478
Kit should never have gone with them.

01:16:58.653 --> 01:17:02.111
- What train were they catching?
- The 4:00 to Baltimore.

01:17:02.290 --> 01:17:05.919
It sounded like the money was buried
in the woods next to the train station.

01:17:06.093 --> 01:17:08.084
Interesting.

01:17:08.629 --> 01:17:11.723
Well, we've got to get there
before they find Kit.

01:17:11.899 --> 01:17:13.423
Okay, hang on!

01:17:16.304 --> 01:17:17.794
[BOTH GRUNTING]

01:17:23.744 --> 01:17:27.009
MISS BOND:
Whoa, nelly!

01:17:27.281 --> 01:17:30.773
Eight, nine, 10.

01:17:30.952 --> 01:17:32.681
[LAUGHS]

01:17:32.853 --> 01:17:34.548
All right, we dig.

01:17:34.722 --> 01:17:36.690
What do you mean "we"?

01:17:40.227 --> 01:17:44.288
Three, two, one.

01:17:45.399 --> 01:17:46.991
I got it now.

01:17:47.368 --> 01:17:49.131
Seven.

01:17:50.771 --> 01:17:52.705
Now, this is it.

01:17:54.375 --> 01:17:55.967
Ow!

01:17:57.812 --> 01:17:59.302
MISS BOND:
Alrighty.

01:18:01.382 --> 01:18:02.644
RUTHIE:
Oh, Miss Bond.

01:18:05.987 --> 01:18:08.353
[BOTH GRUNTING]

01:18:10.524 --> 01:18:12.617
- Miss Bond, no.
- Shh.

01:18:12.793 --> 01:18:15.523
Now, don't you worry.
Everything's gonna be just fine.

01:18:15.696 --> 01:18:17.095
That's Mr. Berk's car.

01:18:17.264 --> 01:18:19.698
I've called the police.
They'll be here any minute.

01:18:19.867 --> 01:18:23.030
Now, stay put, all right?

01:18:35.383 --> 01:18:38.875
- Come on, Ruthie. Let's follow.
- But she said to stay put.

01:18:39.053 --> 01:18:40.543
Come on, hurry.

01:18:52.033 --> 01:18:53.125
RUTHIE:
There she is.

01:18:53.300 --> 01:18:55.530
- Kit.
- What are you doing here?

01:18:55.903 --> 01:18:58.565
- Did anyone see you?
- No. Miss Bond brought us.

01:18:58.739 --> 01:19:00.604
She's gonna help us. Look.

01:19:01.142 --> 01:19:02.666
Is that it?

01:19:03.711 --> 01:19:05.611
Easy, easy.

01:19:06.714 --> 01:19:08.705
[SHOVEL THUDS]

01:19:11.652 --> 01:19:13.643
- That's it. That's it.
- Shovel.

01:19:18.292 --> 01:19:19.657
Come on.

01:19:20.661 --> 01:19:22.322
Yes.

01:19:22.663 --> 01:19:25.154
- They found the box.
- This isn't fair.

01:19:25.332 --> 01:19:29.132
That's our box. That's our money.
That's all that we have.

01:19:29.303 --> 01:19:31.533
STERLING: We'll get it back to you, Kit.
Don't worry.

01:19:31.705 --> 01:19:33.798
- Kit was in your car.
KIT: They're blaming Will.

01:19:33.974 --> 01:19:37.740
Miss Bond called the police.
They're on their way.

01:19:38.512 --> 01:19:43.313
- Wait, where did Miss Bond call from?
- Your house, why?

01:19:45.419 --> 01:19:48.513
Our phone doesn't work, Stirling.

01:19:48.689 --> 01:19:51.283
- Oh, no.
KIT: Oh, no.

01:19:51.559 --> 01:19:53.220
Miss Bond.

01:19:53.394 --> 01:19:56.124
Miss Bond was in on it all along.

01:19:58.666 --> 01:20:00.691
How could I have not have seen it?

01:20:00.868 --> 01:20:03.234
Of course,
every magician has an accomplice.

01:20:03.404 --> 01:20:06.771
- What are you talking about, woman?
- You can't really levitate someone.

01:20:06.941 --> 01:20:09.933
- Unless they're in on the trick.
- Exactly.

01:20:10.511 --> 01:20:12.308
What do we do now?

01:20:12.480 --> 01:20:13.504
[ALL GASP]

01:20:13.681 --> 01:20:16.616
MISS BOND:
- turn around and go back right this...

01:20:18.886 --> 01:20:19.978
Magic.

01:20:21.222 --> 01:20:24.020
Yoo-hoo! Over here.

01:20:24.191 --> 01:20:25.658
She's got a camera.

01:20:26.727 --> 01:20:28.490
MISS BOND:
Kit!

01:20:31.165 --> 01:20:32.655
[GRUNTING]

01:20:35.769 --> 01:20:38.203
Yoo-hoo! Over here.

01:20:38.973 --> 01:20:40.497
Ooh! Ooh!

01:20:42.977 --> 01:20:44.171
No.

01:20:44.345 --> 01:20:46.336
Get up. No, wait. Wait, wait, wait.

01:20:46.680 --> 01:20:49.342
He's taking the loot. Get him.

01:20:52.086 --> 01:20:54.452
[MISS BOND WHIMPERS]

01:21:02.196 --> 01:21:04.061
[GRUNTS]

01:21:06.167 --> 01:21:07.828
Get him. Get him.

01:21:08.002 --> 01:21:11.665
It's all right, Stirling.
No one's gonna hurt you.

01:21:11.839 --> 01:21:14.672
Oh, no. Oh, no. Oh, no.

01:21:14.842 --> 01:21:17.208
[MISS BOND WHIMPERING]

01:21:26.420 --> 01:21:28.718
KIT:
Look, the hobo jungle. We can hide there.

01:21:30.391 --> 01:21:32.052
I've got an idea.

01:21:36.297 --> 01:21:37.457
What are you doing?

01:21:38.165 --> 01:21:40.633
Giving us a head start.

01:21:40.801 --> 01:21:42.234
[MISS BOND PANTING]

01:21:50.044 --> 01:21:54.208
Oh, just let the Kittredges keep their money.

01:21:54.381 --> 01:21:56.941
- Oh, stop it.
- It was never part of our plan.

01:21:57.117 --> 01:22:01.486
Okay, there was $250 in there.
I am not letting them keep nothing.

01:22:01.655 --> 01:22:03.748
You tell your girlfriend to button it.

01:22:03.924 --> 01:22:05.983
BERK: Quiet.
- [WHISPERS] Girlfriend?

01:22:06.160 --> 01:22:09.391
BERK: Oh, don't be so naive, Lucinda.
This is the way it's gonna be from now on.

01:22:09.563 --> 01:22:10.996
[GASPS]

01:22:11.165 --> 01:22:12.291
Oh, lovebirds.

01:22:14.068 --> 01:22:16.832
It's a good thing I read Hobo.

01:22:18.105 --> 01:22:19.766
This way.

01:22:21.342 --> 01:22:23.333
Come on. Come on. Come on.

01:22:36.857 --> 01:22:38.119
Okay, I think we're close.

01:22:38.792 --> 01:22:40.589
[ALL SCREAMING]

01:22:40.761 --> 01:22:42.285
WILL: Kit?
KIT: Will.

01:22:42.463 --> 01:22:44.931
- What are you all doing?
STIRLING: They're chasing us.

01:22:45.099 --> 01:22:47.363
We know who did it.
The Berks and Miss Bond.

01:22:47.534 --> 01:22:49.331
- Berks?
KIT: I always knew it wasn't you.

01:22:49.503 --> 01:22:51.130
- They're after us.
STIRLING: They set you up.

01:22:51.305 --> 01:22:52.465
Come on, let's go.

01:22:58.545 --> 01:23:00.206
- Oh, yeah, that's great.
- Oh!

01:23:00.381 --> 01:23:02.008
Great, huh?

01:23:02.316 --> 01:23:04.910
Boy, sure is a good thing you read Hobo.

01:23:05.085 --> 01:23:06.245
[FREDERICH WHEEZING]

01:23:06.420 --> 01:23:09.856
Come on, let's go.
Come on. Come on. Come on.

01:23:13.427 --> 01:23:15.759
[MISS BOND WHIMPERING]

01:23:24.138 --> 01:23:26.265
Hi. Ahem. Excuse me.

01:23:26.440 --> 01:23:28.340
I was wondering
if somebody could help us.

01:23:28.509 --> 01:23:30.841
Uh, we just happened
to be picnicking nearby...

01:23:31.011 --> 01:23:34.469
...and, uh, it seems that
we have lost our children.

01:23:34.648 --> 01:23:36.013
Oh, I'm sorry to hear that.

01:23:36.183 --> 01:23:39.584
BERK: Yes. So, naturally, we thought
that they had wandered over here.

01:23:39.753 --> 01:23:43.052
Oh, naturally, naturally.
Has anyone seen any lost children?

01:23:43.223 --> 01:23:45.191
Mm-mm.

01:23:48.062 --> 01:23:49.461
No.

01:23:50.364 --> 01:23:53.458
Well, I, uh... I have, um...

01:23:54.068 --> 01:23:55.501
Let's see. Uh...

01:23:55.669 --> 01:23:58.502
Fifty, 70, 80.

01:23:59.073 --> 01:24:01.234
A hundred, uh, dollars...

01:24:01.408 --> 01:24:06.072
...that, uh, I'm sure would probably buy
a lot of food for that baby...

01:24:06.246 --> 01:24:09.340
...and, uh, be able to give some of you
a fresh start.

01:24:09.516 --> 01:24:11.279
So that you might once again become...

01:24:11.685 --> 01:24:14.449
...respectable members
of the community again.

01:24:14.621 --> 01:24:16.782
Ah. Respectable members
of the community?

01:24:17.257 --> 01:24:19.748
- Yes.
- Like you?

01:24:19.927 --> 01:24:21.758
[CHUCKLES]

01:24:21.929 --> 01:24:23.226
- Achoo!
- Shh!

01:24:23.397 --> 01:24:25.228
[GASPS]

01:24:30.738 --> 01:24:34.105
Hello, my little angels. Get them.

01:24:35.042 --> 01:24:36.942
[KIT SHRIEKS]

01:24:37.111 --> 01:24:38.442
STERLING:
Help! Help!

01:24:38.612 --> 01:24:41.080
Help! That's my money! Give it back!

01:24:41.248 --> 01:24:43.409
Not so fast.

01:24:43.584 --> 01:24:44.608
[MEN GRUNTING]

01:24:44.785 --> 01:24:45.911
BERK:
Let go of me.

01:24:47.054 --> 01:24:49.545
KIT:
Aah! No!

01:24:49.723 --> 01:24:51.213
[GROANS]

01:24:53.193 --> 01:24:54.922
Thank you, ma'am.

01:24:55.696 --> 01:24:59.029
- Anytime.
- Lucinda.

01:24:59.500 --> 01:25:01.127
The magic is gone.

01:25:01.301 --> 01:25:03.895
[HOBOS LAUGH]

01:25:05.539 --> 01:25:07.473
No. No.

01:25:07.641 --> 01:25:10.405
No. Unh! Ow.

01:25:12.012 --> 01:25:17.211
Forgive me, Kit.
All of you, I'm so sorry.

01:25:17.384 --> 01:25:19.284
Somehow we convinced ourselves...

01:25:19.453 --> 01:25:23.947
...that desperate times
justify desperate measures.

01:25:24.124 --> 01:25:27.025
Well, Jefferson, I was being naive.

01:25:28.195 --> 01:25:33.497
There we were gallivanting
across the country like Robin Hood...

01:25:33.667 --> 01:25:36.602
...stealing from the rich
to give to the poor.

01:25:37.070 --> 01:25:38.594
When technically...

01:25:38.772 --> 01:25:45.268
...all we really did was steal from the rich
and the poor and kept it.

01:25:47.581 --> 01:25:49.674
Really, that's what we did.

01:25:50.083 --> 01:25:51.914
And you...

01:25:52.352 --> 01:25:56.015
...Jefferson Jasper Renee Berk...

01:25:56.190 --> 01:25:58.454
- Ha, ha!
RUTHIE: Renee?

01:25:58.625 --> 01:25:59.853
[CHILDREN GIGGLE]

01:26:00.027 --> 01:26:01.790
- are no Robin Hood.

01:26:04.231 --> 01:26:07.632
Mac, why don't we go to town,
tell the sheriff we solved the crime spree?

01:26:07.801 --> 01:26:09.530
Tell him it wasn't a hobo after all.

01:26:09.703 --> 01:26:11.671
Yeah. That's right.

01:26:12.339 --> 01:26:14.102
BERK:
Hey, come on. Easy.

01:26:14.875 --> 01:26:17.708
MISS BOND: Goodbye, my friends.
- Bye, Miss Bond.

01:26:19.179 --> 01:26:20.703
Where's Countee, Will?

01:26:21.348 --> 01:26:24.875
You know how they say if you wanna
hide something, you do it in plain sight?

01:26:25.052 --> 01:26:27.646
- Uh-uh.
- Yeah. No.

01:26:28.922 --> 01:26:30.617
Hey, Countee.

01:26:40.167 --> 01:26:42.761
STERLING: You dressed him as a girl?
- I am a girl.

01:26:43.370 --> 01:26:45.235
He's a she? You're a her?

01:26:46.807 --> 01:26:50.004
Everyone,
meet Constance Angel Eudora Garvey.

01:26:50.477 --> 01:26:52.445
Sorry we had to fool you all...

01:26:52.613 --> 01:26:55.446
...but, uh, I promised her daddy
I'd look out for her.

01:26:55.616 --> 01:26:58.881
- It's dangerous for girls to ride the rails.
- Are you mad?

01:26:59.052 --> 01:27:01.953
Of course we're not.
And I like your dress.

01:27:02.689 --> 01:27:05.920
- Thank you.
- Do I have to call you Constance?

01:27:06.226 --> 01:27:07.250
No.

01:27:08.395 --> 01:27:09.692
Good.

01:27:10.030 --> 01:27:13.022
You may be a girl,
but you'll always be a boy to me, Countee.

01:27:13.200 --> 01:27:15.600
Thanks, I think.

01:27:15.769 --> 01:27:17.361
[ALL LAUGH]

01:27:20.007 --> 01:27:21.372
Yeah.

01:27:54.007 --> 01:27:55.474
[GASPS]

01:27:56.643 --> 01:27:58.042
That looks good.

01:27:58.211 --> 01:28:01.544
LOUISE: How exquisite.
- Lovely, Margaret.

01:28:02.015 --> 01:28:04.643
Well, we certainly have a lot
to be thankful for.

01:28:05.686 --> 01:28:07.813
Hear, hear. To Kit.

01:28:07.988 --> 01:28:10.957
We certainly wouldn't still be here
without you.

01:28:12.426 --> 01:28:14.087
To Kit.

01:28:14.528 --> 01:28:16.120
Your father would be so proud.

01:28:18.198 --> 01:28:21.167
And what do you hear from Chicago,
Margaret?

01:28:29.676 --> 01:28:32.076
Kit, would you please pass the beans
to Miss Dooley?

01:28:32.245 --> 01:28:33.576
Yes.

01:28:35.015 --> 01:28:37.108
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

01:28:48.028 --> 01:28:51.361
WILL: Kit.
KIT: Will? Countee?

01:28:52.099 --> 01:28:53.123
Ma'am.

01:28:54.134 --> 01:28:55.931
Sorry to disturb you all...

01:28:56.103 --> 01:28:59.595
...but this being Thanksgiving,
we just wanted to show our thanks.

01:28:59.773 --> 01:29:01.604
It won't be but a minute.

01:29:01.775 --> 01:29:03.402
Come on in.

01:29:03.777 --> 01:29:06.075
- May we?
- Please.

01:29:06.913 --> 01:29:08.039
[GASPS]

01:29:08.215 --> 01:29:10.547
- Oh, Will.
- We didn't know how else to thank you.

01:29:11.051 --> 01:29:13.315
WOMAN: This is yours.
KIT: Hi. Thank you.

01:29:13.487 --> 01:29:14.784
Hi.

01:29:15.722 --> 01:29:17.280
KIT: Hi.
- Hi.

01:29:17.658 --> 01:29:20.126
Can't thank you enough, Miss Kittredge.

01:29:22.429 --> 01:29:25.193
Oh, my good... Will.

01:29:25.365 --> 01:29:27.663
PENNINGTON: You can make a big stew.
- I've never seen...

01:29:27.834 --> 01:29:29.096
WOMAN:
Hi. Thank you very much.

01:29:29.269 --> 01:29:31.737
MAN: Thank you.
MARGARET: Thank you very much.

01:29:32.372 --> 01:29:36.035
[DOGS BARKING IN DISTANCE]

01:29:37.878 --> 01:29:41.006
Oh, please. Please. Don't go. I...

01:29:41.815 --> 01:29:46.411
I can't think of a better way
to celebrate than with all of you.

01:29:46.586 --> 01:29:49.521
Please, won't you join us?

01:29:49.690 --> 01:29:51.885
We'd... We'd be honored.

01:29:54.628 --> 01:29:56.289
Hello?

01:30:00.100 --> 01:30:01.829
Dad?

01:30:03.904 --> 01:30:05.371
Dad!

01:30:05.872 --> 01:30:07.703
[JACK LAUGHS]

01:30:07.874 --> 01:30:09.307
JACK:
Oh!

01:30:09.476 --> 01:30:10.568
Oh!

01:30:11.945 --> 01:30:16.075
Oh, Kit. Come here. Let me look at you.

01:30:17.551 --> 01:30:19.678
Oh, sweetheart.

01:30:23.724 --> 01:30:26.989
You promised me
that you would write to me once a week.

01:30:27.160 --> 01:30:29.253
- And it's been...
- Too long.

01:30:29.429 --> 01:30:30.487
I know, Kit.

01:30:31.198 --> 01:30:34.429
Every day I kept thinking,
"Tomorrow there'll be better news."

01:30:35.502 --> 01:30:37.595
But there never was.

01:30:38.538 --> 01:30:40.165
And then I realized...

01:30:40.540 --> 01:30:42.565
...that if I couldn't face you...

01:30:42.743 --> 01:30:45.803
...or your mother, if I couldn't tell you
what was happening...

01:30:46.413 --> 01:30:48.540
...it was like that old car.

01:30:48.715 --> 01:30:50.239
I was letting it beat me.

01:30:50.884 --> 01:30:52.283
I won't let it beat me, honey.

01:30:55.055 --> 01:30:56.079
MARGARET:
Kit?

01:31:01.394 --> 01:31:02.952
Jack?

01:31:08.902 --> 01:31:11.234
[MARGARET SOBBING]

01:31:11.404 --> 01:31:12.769
JACK:
I'm here.

01:31:20.947 --> 01:31:22.608
And I'm gonna find a job.

01:31:22.949 --> 01:31:24.940
I promise.

01:31:25.252 --> 01:31:26.514
In Chicago?

01:31:30.223 --> 01:31:32.020
JACK:
No, Kit.

01:31:32.359 --> 01:31:34.384
Right here in Cincinnati.

01:31:34.561 --> 01:31:36.825
I'm home to stay.

01:31:42.369 --> 01:31:45.361
[ALL CHATTERING]

01:31:49.042 --> 01:31:50.805
MARGARET:
Want some more juice?

01:31:50.977 --> 01:31:52.467
[TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

01:31:58.185 --> 01:32:00.483
WOMAN:
I just thank you. This is delicious.

01:32:00.654 --> 01:32:02.622
Thank you.

01:32:03.190 --> 01:32:04.214
Mr. Pennington.

01:32:05.592 --> 01:32:07.526
Thank you, sir.

01:32:14.167 --> 01:32:17.227
That son you've got around my age...

01:32:18.004 --> 01:32:19.835
...write him, please...

01:32:20.340 --> 01:32:21.500
...tonight...

01:32:22.042 --> 01:32:23.509
...for me.

01:32:30.750 --> 01:32:33.412
- Excuse me. Everybody.
MAN: Wait, wait.

01:32:33.587 --> 01:32:35.452
Quiet, please, everybody.

01:32:37.490 --> 01:32:40.425
Countee has something she has to say.

01:32:40.861 --> 01:32:42.556
Ready?

01:32:48.902 --> 01:32:53.930
"The cow jumped over the moon."

01:32:54.107 --> 01:32:56.268
What's the cow doing
jumping over the moon?

01:32:56.443 --> 01:32:57.933
- Ha, ha!
COUNTEE: That's just silly.

01:32:58.111 --> 01:33:01.274
All this time I've been trying to read,
and this is what they say?

01:33:01.448 --> 01:33:03.143
[ALL LAUGH]

01:33:03.583 --> 01:33:04.914
Come here. Aw.

01:33:05.085 --> 01:33:06.143
[ALL APPLAUDING]

01:33:06.319 --> 01:33:08.048
I'm proud of you.

01:33:10.457 --> 01:33:11.822
[LAUGHS]

01:33:17.664 --> 01:33:18.722
Hi.

01:33:19.532 --> 01:33:21.363
Kit, sweetheart.

01:33:22.202 --> 01:33:24.329
There's someone here to see you.

01:33:25.171 --> 01:33:27.639
GIBSON:
Margaret Mildred Kittredge.

01:33:27.807 --> 01:33:29.297
Mr. Gibson?

01:33:29.743 --> 01:33:33.008
Here you go, kiddo. Hot off the presses.

01:33:33.179 --> 01:33:35.272
[GASPS]

01:33:37.584 --> 01:33:42.317
- You mean?
- Congratulations, reporter. You're in print!

01:33:42.489 --> 01:33:45.287
Mother, Dad, did you hear it? I'm in print!

01:33:45.458 --> 01:33:50.191
Oh, sweetheart, I knew you could do it.
I always knew.

01:33:50.964 --> 01:33:52.864
Come on, let's show everybody.

01:33:53.934 --> 01:33:58.428
Mr. Gibson, won't you stay for one drink?
It's a holiday. We're all celebrating.

01:33:58.605 --> 01:34:04.134
- Well, perhaps just one, Mrs...
- Oh, it's miss. Miss Dooley.

01:34:04.311 --> 01:34:06.836
- Huh.
- Hmm.

01:34:07.213 --> 01:34:08.976
But you can call me May.

01:34:09.883 --> 01:34:12.283
That was my mother's name.

01:34:12.452 --> 01:34:14.317
Ha. Golly.

01:34:14.487 --> 01:34:17.047
That is a coincidence.

01:34:20.393 --> 01:34:23.624
GIBSON: Well, what sort of drinks
are you preparing tonight?

01:34:25.198 --> 01:34:29.066
KIT: <i>That November,</i>
<i>we didn't dwell on what we'd lost.</i>

01:34:29.235 --> 01:34:32.261
<i>Rather, we celebrated what we had.</i>

01:34:32.439 --> 01:34:33.565
Is everyone ready?

01:34:34.107 --> 01:34:35.131
Yes.

01:34:38.144 --> 01:34:39.907
All right, then.

01:34:47.687 --> 01:34:49.621
We are now one.

01:34:50.824 --> 01:34:51.916
[CURTIS SQUEAKS]

01:34:52.092 --> 01:34:54.117
[ALL GASP]

01:34:54.294 --> 01:34:56.956
RUTHIE: Oh, my gosh.
- I'm one with the monkey.

01:34:57.130 --> 01:34:58.324
Don't tell my mother.

01:34:58.498 --> 01:34:59.988
[ALL LAUGH]

01:35:00.967 --> 01:35:04.494
No, wait. We haven't done
the sacred Treehouse pledge.

01:35:05.438 --> 01:35:08.202
KIT: <i>The Depression had changed</i>
<i>each one of our lives.</i>

01:35:09.442 --> 01:35:13.606
<i>And while it made us struggle,</i>
<i>it also made us strong.</i>

01:35:13.780 --> 01:35:15.611
KIT & RUTHIE:
Gwanga, gwanga, galoolie.

01:35:15.782 --> 01:35:18.512
COUNTEE & STERLING:
Gwanga, gwanga, galoolie.

01:35:18.685 --> 01:35:20.007
Kit, look,
the monkey's got your camera.

01:35:20.954 --> 01:35:23.514
KIT:
<i>Now, no matter what life had in store...</i>

01:35:23.690 --> 01:35:25.021
[CAMERA CLICKS]

01:35:25.191 --> 01:35:27.284
<i>... I was ready.</i>

